<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 15:30 GMT, October 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has said
that it is training Muslim militants from the Palestinian Hamas
and Islamic Jihad movements in Lebanon, local weekly Haramoun
magazine reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the magazine, Sheikh Naee'm Kassem,
Hezbollah deputy secretary-general, said the groups had
coordinated in the past. (Lebanon-Hezbollah)
----
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The U.S. has signaled that it wants a negotiated
solution to the squabble with the European Union (EU) over a
two-billion-U.S.-dollar oil deal signed between Iran and the
French oil group Total last month.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials have suggested that the Clinton administration
might waive sanctions against Total if European governments agree
to toughen their approach to Iran, an article in the latest
European Report, a twice-weekly publication, said
today. (EU-US-Total)
----
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The Afghan northern alliance forces defending
their stronghold of Mazar-e-Sharif have repulsed Islamic Taliban
militia's offensive from the northern side of the city, Pakistan
Television (PTV) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the anti-Taliban alliance also claimed that they
 had also pushed back the hard-line student militia from the east
side of Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north of Kabul, PTV
said. (Afghan-Fighting)
----
</P>
<P>
BARCELONA -- Spain's Princess Cristina, the youngest daughter
of King Huan Carlos, married Olympic handball player Inaki
Urdangarin in a grand ceremony Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,500 guests, including members of the European royal
families and Spain's top religious and business figures, attended
the wedding ceremony at the Santa Eulalia Cathedral, which for the
past two centuries, was the first of its kind in the eastern city
of Spain. (Spain-Princess-Marriage)
----
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko Saturday
asked the republic's prosecutor-general to release the jailed
journalist whose detention has aborted the president's trip to
Russian cities of Lipetsk and Yaroslavl, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Journalist Pavel Sheremet was kept in prison in Belarus' Grodno
and charged with illegally crossing the Belarussian-Lithuanian
border.(Belarus-Russia-Journalist)
----
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Astronauts aboard U.S. space shuttle Atlantis have
visually pinpointed two impact points that damaged the
air-tightness of Russian space station Mir.
</P>
<P>
The finding, said a report from the Russian ground mission
control, was relayed back on Friday night Russian summer time
while Atlantis was hovering around Mir more than 70 meters
away.(Russia-Mir)
----
</P>
