<HEADLINE> Serbian Radio, TV Stations Strike to Protest Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Employees from the radio and
television stations of the Serbian capital Pale began a general
strike today to protest the NATO-led Stablization Force's (SFOR)
capture of the radio station and three TV transmitters three days
ago.
</P>
<P>
According to Novinska Agencija Tanjug, radio and television
stations from Bijeljina and the Trebinje technological center also
participated in the strike.
</P>
<P>
The Information Minister of the Republic Srpska, Svetlana
Ssilegovic commented on the strike today, saying the Serbian
government understood the strikers' motives and backed their
actions.
</P>
<P>
She also said the government hopes that the international
community will respect the laws of the republic and stop the
punitive actions against the Serbian people.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic Srpska, Aleksa Buha, today
charged the international community of becoming more deeply
involved in every aspect of the republic's life, saying SFOR is in
fact operating a military occupation of the republic.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 SFOR troops took the three transmission towers
Wednesday. According to NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, the
troops will hand the towers over to new management, which he
defined as the parties supporting the Republic Srpska president.
</P>
<P>
The aim of SFOR's action is to assist the international high
representative in ensuring that the media in the republic reflects
international norms of professional media conduct and fully
supports the goals of the Dayton peace accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
