<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Political Events in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The following is a chronology
of major events in Nepali politics since 1990:
</P>
<P>
From January to April, 1990 -- The Popular Movement was
launched against the Panchayat (partyless) system with the
objective of introducing a multi-party system. Many were killed,
injured or arrested during the violent demonstrations and strikes.
</P>
<P>
April 8 -- King Birendra announced that the 30-year ban on
political parties was to be ended and a commission to study
constitutional reform was to be established.
</P>
<P>
April 15 -- King Birendra accepted the resignation of Prime
Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand, dismissed the Council of
Ministers (cabinet) and announced the dissolution of the Panchayat
system.
</P>
<P>
April 19 -- An interim government headed by Krishna Prasad
Bhattarai was formed with the main task of preparing a new
constitution. The new prime minister announced that a general
election would be held on a multi-party basis within a year.
</P>
<P>
May 12, 1991 -- A general election was held, during which the
Nepali Congress (NC) won a comfortable majority.
</P>
<P>
May 29 -- Girija Prasad Koirala, general secretary of the NC,
took office as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
March 7, 1994 -- G.P. Koirala resigned and ordered new
elections after losing a key parliamentary vote due to the absence
of 36 NC MPs.
</P>
<P>
November 15 -- The mid-term election was held and a hung
parliament emerged during which no single party commanded a
majority.
</P>
<P>
November 29 -- Man Mohan Adhikari, president of the Communist
Party of Nepal (United Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML), the largest
party in Parliament, formed a one-party government.
</P>
<P>
September 10, 1995 -- M.M. Adhikari resigned after losing a
no-confidence motion.
</P>
<P>
September 11 -- Sher Bahadur Deuba was named prime minister of
a three-party coalition.
</P>
<P>
March 6, 1997 -- S.B. Deuba resigned after losing a confidence
motion tabled by himself. Prior to this, he survived two
no-confidence motions.
</P>
<P>
March 12 -- Lokendra Bahadur Chand was sworn in as prime
minister of a three-party coalition government.
</P>
<P>
September 22 -- The main opposition party Nepali Congress
registered a no-confidence motion against the government.
</P>
<P>
October 4 -- Chand resigned after the Lower House passed by
107-94 votes the no-confidence motion against his government. King
Birendra accepted his resignation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
