<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Youth Urged to Go Into Informal Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Education, Sports and
Culture Minister Gabriel Machinga today implored school leavers
to go to the informal sector for their future, as jobs are
increasingly becoming scarce in the formal market.
</P>
<P>
He said the informal sector in Zimbabwe was expanding and now
employing more people.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a meeting of Bikita Informal Sector
Association in south Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"There is need to promote the informal sector because that is
where most jobs are now coming from, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Whereas in 1996 the formal sector employed 1.26 million
people, the informal sector employed a higher number of 1.56
million the same year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe churns out about 300,000 school leavers annually.
</P>
<P>
"Of all those children going out of school, only 25 percent
get jobs. The other 75 percent simply go into the world because
jobs are scarce, their only hope lies in the informal sector," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Besides jobs being scarce, education in Zimbabwe was
increasingly becoming expensive for both the government and the
parents, said Machinga. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
