<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Ruling Party Demands Law-Awareness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's ruling Zanu (PF)
today held a one-day conference to discuss the party constitution
and the country's national constitution in Gweru, central
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Zanu (PF) Secretary for Legal Affairs Eddison Zvobgo said
misunderstandings in the party arose because provincial executive
members did not understand the constitution of the party.
</P>
<P>
He said if party cadres did not understand the rules and
regulations of the party, Zanu (PF) would always be bogged down
with squabbles.
</P>
<P>
"This should not happen in a party which is as old as ours,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The conference is being attended by commissars, legal
secretaries and other executive members from the party's 10
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Zvobgo stressed it was important for all executive members to
understand the country's national constitution and the party's
constitution so that they would follow proper procedures when
dealing with matters in their respective provinces.
</P>
<P>
He urged Zanu (PF) members not to plant seeds of disunity among
party members, because the 1987 unity accord signed by President
Robert Mugabe and Vice-President Joshua Nkomo was "irrevocable".
</P>
<P>
The accord saw the merger of the country's main rival political
parties, the ruling Zanu (PF) and Nkomo's Zapu (PF).
</P>
<P>
Zvobgo said the legal conference was not capable of amending
the party's constitution as that could only be done by congress.
</P>
<P>
The conference will also discuss the restructuring of the
party, salient provisions of the constitution, the disciplinary
code of conduct, the legal framework of local government and
national elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana Holds Referendum on Lowering Voting Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Botswana people went to
the polls today for a referendum to decide on key constitutional
changes, South African media reported.
</P>
<P>
The proposed amendments would lower the voting age from 21 to
18, allow citizens resident outside Botswana to vote and
introduce an independent electoral commission, South African
Press Association said.
</P>
<P>
A fourth amendment to the constitution, limiting the
president's term of office to ten years, was recently approved by
parliament and would not be subject to a referendum.
</P>
<P>
Botswana has had only two presidents -- the late Seretse Khama
who died in office after serving for 14 years and Ketumile Masire
who has been in power for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
Although there is wide speculation that Masire, 72, will not
seek re-election in 1999, legally he would be able to serve for
two more five-year terms because the constitutional amendment is
not retroactive.
</P>
<P>
The referendum is seen by observers as a test for President
Masire's ruling Botswana Democratic Party (BDP), whose majority
support has been declining in recent polls, said The Citizen
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The BDP, which holds 31 of the 44 seats in parliament, has
been formulating changes to the constitution since last year
following pressure from its youth members and opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
Lowering the voting age could reduce BDP's share of voter
support, reports said.
</P>
<P>
According to official projections, lowering the voting age
will add eligible 53,000 voters.
</P>
<P>
The 1,600 voting stations, many of them in remote areas of the
Kalahari desert and the northwest of Botswana, opened at 6.30
a.m. local time (0430 GMT) and would close at 7 p.m. (1700 GMT)
today.
</P>
<P>
Only registered voters above the age of 21 were allowed to
take part in today's referendum.
</P>
<P>
Results from the remote areas would not be available in the
capital of Gaborone until late Sunday or early Monday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed amendments have already been debated in
parliament and the ruling BDP and opposition Botswana National
Front have voiced their approval for the changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
