<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Reassured of Enduring Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Both Joaqium Chissano, President
of Mozambique and Afonso Dhlakama, Chairman of National
Resistance Movement of Mozambique (NRM), the biggest opposition
party, agreed today that the country could enjoy an endurable
peace.
</P>
<P>
Chissano and Dhlakama made the remark on an occasion marking
the fifth anniversary of the signing of the Rome General Protocol
for Peace between the government and NRM, according to Mozambican
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Chissano said that the consolidated peace the country is
enjoying is not a fruit of either the government or any
individual, but a result of the combined effort of the whole
society.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is no condition for a renewal of war in the
country, as no one in or outside of the country wish to see
another war in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Though there are still a few armed groups hindering the free
flow of personnel and materials, they could by no means pose as a
threat to the peace in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chissano added that consensus should be reached for a joint
action on these armed groups.
</P>
<P>
Dhlakama also excluded the possibility of war in the country,
stressing that national reconciliation is the key to consolidate
peace.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the whole society should bear the
responsibility for peace and democracy in Mozambique, adding that
"peace depends on the understanding among the people in the
country. "
</P>
<P>
The president and the NRM leader urged people of all walks in
the society to join hands to keep the country away from war.
</P>
<P>
Dhlakama denied that there are still NRM armed personnel
operating in the forests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
