<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Considers Sanctions against S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council may impose a global oil, arms and travel embargo against
Sierra Leone to press the military junta to surrender as a draft
resolution is reportedly under discussion.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here quoted UN diplomats as saying Friday
that the 15-member body aimed to adopt the measures before a west
African regional summit next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A British drafted resolution currently circulating calls on
the military junta which seized power in the May 25 coup this
year to "take immediate steps to relinquish power in Sierra Leone
and make way for the restoration of the democratically elected
government."
</P>
<P>
A similar demand was also made by the United States Friday.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions aim to support the efforts of the 16-nation
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) targeted at
reinstating the government of ousted President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
However, the measures envisaged are less broad than the west
African regional package of sanctions adopted at the end of
August.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the international sanctions would
remain in force until the Kabbah government and "constitutional
order" are restored.
</P>
<P>
The council draft notably calls for a ban on the sale or
supply of "petroleum or petroleum products or arms and related
material of all types, including weapons and ammunition, military
vehicles and equipment, paramilitary equipment and spare parts".
</P>
<P>
It also provides for international travel restrictions against
"members of the military junta in Sierra Leone and adult members
of their families".
</P>
<P>
But humanitarian assistance will not be affected by the
proposed embargo.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft resolution under discussion, a
committee will be established to monitor the implementation of
the sanctions against Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
African leaders, including President Kabbah, were pressing the
council to agree to the possible use of force to ensure the
application of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
This point, however, had not yet been agreed by council
members.
</P>
<P>
The west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) ordered by ECOWAS
to enforce economic sanctions and embargo on Sierra Leone has
announced that it will attack any violators of the ECOWAS
decision.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG has reportedly dropped bombs against ships accused of
unloading arms and ammunition at the port of Freetown, capital of
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Two days ago, the force called on international organizations
intending to deliver humanitarian aid to Sierra Leone to get
clearance from it so as to be protected and assisted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Premier's Visit to Tighten Ties With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral arrived in Uganda today to pay a two-day state visit
to the east African country.
</P>
<P>
He was received at the Entebbe international airport by
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and other high-ranking
officials.
</P>
<P>
Gujral later today held private talks with Museveni and other
Ugandan officials.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Gujral accompanied by a group of
high-ranking officials and a delegation of businessmen and
industrialists will visit local factories.
</P>
<P>
He will unveil a monument to commemorate M.K. Gandhi, late
leader of Indian National Independence Movement at Jinja, 80
kilometers east of Kampala.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his visit, Gujral will hold a joint press
conference together with Museveni.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and India have a long trade and social relationship.
However in 1972, the former Ugandan President Idi Amin expelled
more than 80,000 Asians mostly Indians who controlled the core
investments in the country and gave their property to Africans.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, this policy of putting the economy in the hands
of Africans bungled and Uganda's once envied economy in the
region went down.
</P>
<P>
However when Museveni captured power in 1986 he launched a
campaign to lure back the expelled and dispossessed Asians to
Uganda. Many of them have regained their property and the
decaying factories have been revived.
</P>
<P>
Now there are a number of heavy and light factories all over
the country which are built by the new surge of Indian investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
