<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-04 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Cruise Liner Catches Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- British helicopters and Cypriot
police helped evacuate tourists and crew members today from the
Cypriot registered cruise liner "Romantica" that caught fire some
100 kilometers off the southern coast of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
All 487 passengers and 186 crew members of the cruise ship
were safely evacuated and eventually arrived at the Limassol Port.
Most of the passengers on the three-day cruise to Egypt and
Israel were from Britain, Germany and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Romantica, a 10,500-tonne Cypriot ship, was returning to
Limassol port from Port Said, Egypt when it caught fire.
</P>
<P>
The British forces in Cyprus sent two of its Wessex
helicopters from Akrotiri military base to the scene which
helped transfer the passengers to another Cypriot registered
cruise liner "Princessa Victoria," which arrived at the scene of
the incident 45 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Minister of Communication and Works Leontios
Ierodiakonou said he did not believe the fire was the result of
arson. He said the ship fulfilled all safety requirements.
</P>
<P>
Police Chief Panicos Hadjiloizou told reporters today that
the Cyprus police have drawn up an action plan and began
investigations into the cause of the fire. 
</P>
