<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recruitment to Strengthen Liberia's National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles Taylor
said today he would soon begin recruiting able-bodied Liberians
for training to strengthen national security.
</P>
<P>
"We shall shortly order the massive recruitment and training
of able-bodied men and women to protect and defend the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of this country," Taylor
said on his private radio station in the capital Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, who was just back from his visit to Libya a day ago,
said the plan would include the restructuring of the national
army and the Armed Forces of Liberia (AFL).
</P>
<P>
Restructure of Liberia's army and security force is the final
phase in the implementation of the Abuja peace accord which
brought to an end the country's seven-year-old bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
The west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG, which has
taken charge for ensuring security in Liberia since its
successful disarmament and demobilization of the warring factions
in the country, will help in the restructuring and training job,
according to the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
But Taylor said his government would go ahead with the
restructuring of the army, arguing that the task lied within his
constitutional authority.
</P>
<P>
"We will wait for no one to restructure the AFL because it is
in my constitutional responsibility to do so," he said.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's Defense Minister Daniel Chea last month backed out
on an attempt to restructure the Liberian army after ECOMOG Force
Commander Major-General Victor Malu warned that the task was the
responsibility of the force.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace accord, ECOMOG will remain in Liberia for six
months after the elected government took office on August 2 for
the restructuring and training mission.
</P>
<P>
But the job did not begin as scheduled for some reasons and
ECOMOG is expected to extend its stay in the country.
</P>
<P>
Taylor returned home Friday following a medical trip to South
Africa, a two-day visit to Nigeria and one to Libya as well as a
number of other African countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
