<HEADLINE> Africa Enjoys Better Image, Ethiopian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian President Negasso
Gidada said today that Africa's wretched image is now changing
for the better thanks to a host of measures being taken by
African governments and indigenous institutions.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by the Ethiopian president in his
opening address to the 7th General Assembly of the All Africa
Conference of Churches (AACC) which opened at the United Nations
Conference Center here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The continued implementation of economic reform programs and
the strengthening of market-based and private sector-driven
policies, among others, have greatly contributed to the steady
recovery of the economies of a number of african countries,"
President Negasso said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "similarly, the process of transition to
democratic systems of government in many parts of the continent
has created a conducive situation for peace and stability and for
a favorable climate for economic and social progress."
</P>
<P>
He paid tribute to the many contributions made by the African
churches, which include the preservation of the African cultures
and the spiritual guidance to the liberation struggle from the
yoke of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
As the millennium closes in, he said the churches of Africa
"have a spiritual and moral obligation to exert maximum effort
towards the mobilization of resources from both inside and
outside Africa to address the pressing and immediate social and
economic needs of our fellow Africans."
</P>
<P>
Abune Paulos, patriarch of the Ethiopian orthodox church, on
his part said on the threshold of the 21st century churches in
Africa "should muster the resolve to address the social and
spiritual problems of the African peoples in the continent and
throughout the diaspora."
</P>
<P>
Desmond Tutu, President of AACC, in his speech stressed the
cooperation between African churches and governments, saying that
churches in Africa should cooperate closely with governments in
the continent.
</P>
<P>
The 7-day 7th assembly of the AACC is being attended by more
than 800 participants from about 150 member churches from nearly
40 African countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
