<HEADLINE> Jordan Expects Israel to Release More Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official said
here today that Jordan expected Israel to release more
Palestinian prisoners following the release of Shiekh Ahmed
Yassin, founder of the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas).
</P>
<P>
The release of Yassin would hopefully be the beginning of
"something good," Samir Mutawe, Minister of State for
Information Affairs, told the press after a regular cabinet
meeting, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Mutawe, Yassin would return to the Gaza Strip
within a week.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not elaborate on Israel's possible steps on
Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Israel released ailing Yassin, who was jailed by Israel in 1989
and spent eight years of a life sentence for ordering attacks by
Hamas guerrillas against Israeli targets, on Jordanian King
Hussein's demand on September 30.
</P>
<P>
Hussein has expressed the hope that the release of Yassin would
be the first step of a series of Israeli actions that might help
reactivate the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
During the process of Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations
which has been stalled since Israel started to build Jewish
settlements in Arab East Jerusalem in March, hundreds of
Palestinians, including Hamas members, were jailed by Israel for
wide-ranging reasons.
</P>
<P>
The number of the Palestinians jailed by Israel has not been
available till now.
</P>
<P>
Hamas was established in 1987 to fight against Israel's
occupation of Palestine. Most Hamas political bureau members live
in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and is
one of the only two Arab countries that conceived peace
with the Jewish state. 
</P>
