<HEADLINE> Nigerian City to Recycle Solid Wastes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Oyo state government has
decided to negotiate with foreign companies on how to recycle
wastes generated in the capital city of Ibadan, the second
largest in west Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Modalities are now being worked out for the processing of
solid wastes into in-organic fertilizer, according to Alhaji
Raimi Gbadamosi, general manager of the Ibadan Solid Waste
Management Authority (ISWMA).
</P>
<P>
ISWMA, set up four months ago, has received the state
government approval to negotiate with some foreign companies for
this end, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The general manager expected to begin commercialization of the
locally produced fertilizer six months after the take-off of the
project, adding that this would further alleviate the hardship
suffered by farmers in the procurement of fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the state government had since June
committed the sum of about 24,000 U.S. Dollars to refuse
disposal.
</P>
<P>
However, he observed that ISWMA's equipment was inadequate to
cope with the volume of waste generated within Ibadan metropolis
and its environs.
</P>
<P>
He also regretted at the uncooperative attitude of the people
as the pay-as-you-dump policy had not been received well.
</P>
<P>
People would rather dump their refuse by the roadside than pay
to have them evacuated by officials of the authority, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
