<HEADLINE> Ethiopia: Management Matters in Animal Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Wild life in Ethiopia's
Awash National Park, one of the foremost tourist attractions in
the country, is reportedly dwindling for lack of proper care and
protection, the Ethiopian News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, cattle herders have now settled over
two-thirds of the protected area in search of grazing land due to
rain shortage in the locality.
</P>
<P>
The unwarranted settlement in the park has greatly impacted
the reproduction and the overall life style of the animals. The
habitat for over 580 mammals and bird species is now flooded with
flocks of cattle resulting in dwindling number of the much
coveted wild life.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a study as saying that the number of gazelle
in the park has dropped from 1500 to 215, deer from 600 to 84 and
that of oryx from 400 to 925 in a period of two decades. At the
same time zebras and bushbucks have long disappeared from the
park.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an earlier report by the Ethiopian News Agency said
that the number of animals in another national park in the
northern part of the country has increased due to discouragement
of the practice of tree-felling, protection of the forest from
fire as well as employment of 14 guards.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, in Humera Park in the northern part
of the country, the number of elephants which has been limited
less than 70 in the past has reached 170 now.
</P>
<P>
The report said, the number of other wild animals such as
leopard, greater kudu, clip springer and bush duiker existing in
the park has also increased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
