<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Compensations Committee
has approved the remitting of 136.355 million U.S. dollars as a
second set of compensations for 54,542 Egyptians who left Iraq
during the Gulf War, the Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The committee also agreed, at its recent meeting in Geneva, to
pay the first batch worth 46 million dollars, from which 18,439
Egyptian citizens will benefit, according to Ahmed Goma, the
deputy assistant foreign minister for international political
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The sums will be remitted to Egypt by the end of this month, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. committee has set aside a fund of up to 823 million
dollars to pay Egyptian victims in six installments.
</P>
<P>
The funds were made available by an oil-for-food deal signed
last May by Iraq and the U.N. which enables Baghdad to sell 2
billion dollars worth of oil over six months to raise money for
food, medicine and compensation funds.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was defeated by Western allied forces in the Gulf War in
1991 and the U.N. imposed sanctions against Iraq for its 1990
invasion of Kuwait. 
