<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli-Canadian
relationship has been damaged by an attack on Hamas (the Islamic
Resistance Movement of Palestine) leader last week in Jordanian
capital of Amman, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted political sources here as saying that only two
weeks ago, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy reached an
agreement with his Canadian counterpart Lloyd Axworthy to enhance
cooperation between Israel and Canada and Canadian Prime Minister
Jean Chretien accepted an invitation to visit Israel soon.
</P>
<P>
But now the Canadian prime minister's visit to Israel is in
doubt, the radio quoted the sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hamas leader Khaled Mashal was attacked and injured on
September 25 by two attackers holding Canadian passports which
were proved to be forged ones.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Jordanian police has identified the two
attackers, one from Jerusalem, and another from a charity
organization in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The report said they were sent by Israeli security service
Mossad to conduct this attack, and a total of eight agents
entered into Jordan for this mission, three of them now have
taken refugee at the Israeli Embassy in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian authority so far has not confirmed whether the two
attackers are agents of Mossad or not, saying only that the
investigation is still going on.
</P>
<P>
Canada has taken this matter very seriously, and recalled its
ambassador to Israel Thursday for "immediate consultations."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Foreign Ministry has expressed regret over the
recall of Canadian envoy and hopes to maintain friendly
relations with Canada.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli government officials, including Prime minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Foreign Minister David Levy, have so far
made no comment on this matter. 
</P>
