<HEADLINE> Britain, United States Heading for Row Over Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain and the United States are
heading for a diplomatic row over the use of British companies to
circumvent international economic sanctions against Libya.
</P>
<P>
Some well-placed sources were quoted by the Observer newspaper
as saying that some of the equipment supplied to Libya might be
used in the manufacture of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has already taken legal action against a
number of American companies which have supplied computers and
pipeline equipment to Libya through British companies.
</P>
<P>
However, Washington has expressed concern that there had been
no similar prosecutions in Britain with U.S. Customs director
Michael Turner criticizing the London government's stance on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign governments, including the British, cooperate in
helping make cases against American companies, but when it comes
to making prosecutions in their own countries, they are
reluctant," Turner said.
</P>
<P>
In response, a British Foreign Office spokesman said, "No one
has been more vigorous in imposing United Nations sanctions than
us."
</P>
<P>
"If we had any reason to believe that British companies had
breached our obligations, we would take immediate action," the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
It was revealed recently that a British company had linked to
U.S. investigation into alleged violations of U.N. economic
sanctions against Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
