discussed the recent attack in Amman against a Hamas leader, but
shunning comments on the event which led to diplomatic strife with
Canada.
</P>
<P>
The government "refrains at this time from commenting on media
reports regarding activities against Hamas leader Khaled Mashal,"
said a statement issued after the first cabinet meeting since the
Jewish New Year.
</P>
<P>
Mashal, a political leader of Hamas, was attacked on September
25 by two "tourists" holding forged Canadian passports. Jordanian
police arrested the attackers and said they are Israeli agents.
</P>
<P>
Local press and politicians have pointed that if the attempted
attack proved to be the work of the intelligence agency Mossad,
then Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu must bear the
responsibility as he was powered to issue the final order for such
operations.
</P>
<P>
The statement criticized the reports against Netanyahu that he
should resign if he ordered this attack, saying those
"irresponsible attacks at home on the Prime Minister...would harm
vital national interests of the State of Israel."
</P>
<P>
"False charges are being published, thus cynically exploiting a
situation in which the government is, at present, refraining from
comment," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government, declaring the use of its passports by
foreign agents to be unacceptable, recalled its ambassador to
Israel on Friday, threatening to consider further actions against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces have been hunting Hamas, or the Islamic
Resistance Movement which claimed responsibility for the two
bombing events against Israelis in July and September in
Jerusalem, killing at least 26 people. 
</P>
