<HEADLINE> Symposium on Yangtze River Area Development To Be Held in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- A symposium on economic
development along the Yangtze River, China, will be held in Hong
Kong Tuesday, a spokesman for the World Trade Centers Association
(WTCA) said this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told a news briefing in the Foreign
Correspondents' Club: "As one of the most important topics of the
28th General Assembly of the WTCA, the Symposium on Economic
Development along the Yangtze River has been singled out for the
first time at an international conference."
</P>
<P>
The four-day annual meeting of the WTCA will start Monday, with
participation of more than 1,000 representatives from over 90
countries and regions. It is expected to focus on strengthening
international cooperation for economic development.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that Yangtze River Basin delegations
from major cities -- Chongqing, Shanghai and Wuhan, and major
provinces -- Sichuan, Hubei, Anhui, Zhejiang and Jiangsu, and two
state-run giant corporations -- Yangtze Development Corporation
and Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development Corporation will
attend the Symposium on Economic Development along the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press on their financial and investment policy
measures for the development along the Yangtze River, the leaders
of the delegations said at the same news briefing: "After years of
development, the Yangtze River Basin has emerged as an industrial
galley for manufacturing industry and raw materials industry."
</P>
<P>
"Steel, petrochemical and automobile industries have been
developed as pillars," they told reporters, adding that "new
industries like new naturals, bio-engineering, micro-electronics
and telecommunications are growing rapidly."
</P>
<P>
Following the successful implementation of the opening-up
policy along the coastal area, the Chinese government has decided
to shift its strategic emphasis to the development along the
6,300-kilometer Yangtze River, the longest river in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
