<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Secretary in France Over South Command, Oil Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States Defense
Secretary William Cohen is on a four-day visit here since Saturday
over an Iran-France oil deal and a U.S.-France dispute over NATO's
South Command.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said he will remind France of Washington's concern that
Iran could obtain technology for producing massive destruction
weapons with currency earned in oil deals with foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
And he is expected to refuse France's demand that the NATO
South Command be headed by a European.
</P>
<P>
The French oil giant Total and its coalition partners, Russia's
Gazprom, Malaysia' Petronas signed a 2 billion dollar contract
with Iran last month on jointly developing an offshore gas field
in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The deal is the biggest foreign investment in Iran since the
1979 revolution and defies U.S. threats that the contract would
trigger punitive action.
</P>
<P>
Under the Iran-Libya Sanctions Act passed in 1996,
U.S. President Bill Clinton is required to impose sanctions on any
foreign company investing more than 20 million dollars a year in
the two countries' energy industries.
</P>
<P>
Only one week after the Total deal, the Pentagon decided to
send the aircraft carrier Nimitz to the Persian Gulf. The
73,000-ton carrier, which usually carrier about 50 F-14 and F/A-18
combat aircrafts, would arrive the region by mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Iran raided on based of the Mujahideen Khalq, the
main Iranian opposition group. One of the bases was inside the
no-fly zone imposed by the United States and its allies since 1992
over southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Cohen is also due to meet French Defense
Minister Alain Richard. The discussion is likely to include
U.S. rejection of French demands that the United States turn over
command of southern NATO forces based in Naples to a European
officer.
</P>
<P>
France has put on hold its earlier-announced plans to rejoin
NATO's military structure, which it pulled out in 1966, because of
fight over the south command.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been heading the South Command and two
other supreme strategic commanding seats of NATO. Germany, Spain
and Italy also want the South Command to be headed by a European.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
