<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Ownership Beneficial to Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese-American scholar
pointed out that owning to its public-ownership dominated economy,
China has advantages in controlling pollution and coordinate economic
development and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 14th annual International Pittsburgh Coal
Conference and Workshop of Clean Coal Technology and Coal
Utilization that convened here late last month, Chiang
Shiao-hung, director of the Center for Energy Studies at the
Pittsburgh University, said both developed and developing
countries are challenged by pollution problems caused by coal
mining, transportation and burning.
</P>
<P>
The best solution is to popularize the coal washing technology,
renovate emission installment of automobiles and use pipeline for
coal transport.
</P>
<P>
Because of different economic system, Chiang said, the developed
countries have a hard time for using the private land to build up
oil, gas and coal pipelines.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China has no such headaches. The government can
mobilize the whole society in a well-organized manner to take part
in environmental protection projects. It can organize enterprises
to undertake environmental-friendly energy projects and popularize
anti-pollution technologies.
</P>
<P>
Chiang suggested China try to use pipeline to transport coal in
the future as it will encounter no problems in using the land for
such projects.
</P>
<P>
Chun Sun W, a senior advisor to the Department of Energy of the
United States said that China became the world number one coal
producer last year with 1.3 billion tons of output.
</P>
<P>
It has great potential in coal utilization and a high-level
research team to work on coal-related pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign specialists agreed that China has made headways in
both building up a legal framework for environmental protection
and promoting the coordinated development of national economy and
environmental protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CNN Plan to Directly Collect Fee in SKorea Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government will
not allow the U.S. Cable News Network (CNN) to directly collect
fees in the country, the Ministry of Information said in a report
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
In the report submitted to the parliament, the ministry said it
will outlaw the CNN's plan to charge South Korean hotels and
motels which can receive the signal from the 24-hour cable news
channel.
</P>
<P>
The ministry justified its decision by criticizing some foreign
satellite news and entertainment channels for sending their signal
to South Korea without permission.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, however, said that it will not regulate the
satellite services of Japan's NHK and Hong Kong's Star TV, which
provide their programs free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
