<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Check to Streamline China's Financial and Tax Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The State Council, China's
highest governing body, will launch a nationwide check on taxes,
financial operations and prices this fall in order to ensure sound
financial order to support the country's economic upsurge.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Liu Zhongli addressed a national meeting of
senior financial officials and urged governments at all levels to
participate in related efforts in order to ensure the
authoritativeness and precision of the check.
</P>
<P>
The check will begin this year and will basically be completed
by next Spring Festival, or the Chinese Lunar New Year's Day,
which falls on January 28, 1998. The check will focus on
violations of the country's tax and price laws during the
1996-1997 fiscal year, as well as on serious cases in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
Institutions subject to the check will include major
contributors of value-added, consumption and income taxes, as well
as financial and insurance institutions, non-banking organizations,
grain departments, government enterprises, and shareholding,
collective and private companies with poor financial management.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the check, a financial management method with Chinese
characteristics, reflects the needs of the ongoing macro-control
effort and will help streamline the legal system governing the
country's financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The central government will increase the effectiveness of the
check by abolishing internal checks completed without the
participation of impartial organizations, and will further
strengthen enforcement of the country's financial laws, according
to Liu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
