<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Kazak Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng met
today with Muhtar Alteinbaev, defense minister of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
Li said that President Jiang Zemin and the Chinese government
attach great importance to the development of friendly and
cooperative Sino-Kazak relations. He noted that bilateral
relations have developed smoothly over the past five years since
the two countries established diplomatic links.
</P>
<P>
Li said the recent petroleum and natural gas cooperation
agreement inked by the two nations marked a new stage in the
development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier noted that his recent brief visit to
Kazakhstan achieved important results. Li said that he and
Kazak President Nursultan Abishevich Nazarbayev discussed and
reached a consensus on a wide-range of topics.
</P>
<P>
"We foresee broad prospects for Sino-Kazak relations, with
bilateral cooperation in the petroleum and natural gas sector
injecting new substantial content to two-way friendship and
cooperation," said Li.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China and Kazakhstan share a 1,700 km. border,
and expressed his belief that the border will serve as a link in
bilateral friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Alteinbaev said that Kazak President Nazarbayev places great
importance on friendship and cooperation between the two countries
and their armed forces. He also pointed to the great significance
of the bilateral petroleum and gas cooperation agreement.
</P>
<P>
Alteinbaev said the Kazak government treasures friendly
relations with China, and noted that his government has
steadfastly opposed national splittism in any form and prohibits
any person in Kazakhstan from carrying out activities designed
to split China.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the current visit has enabled him to
acquire a better understanding of China's construction and efforts
to build its military. He also expressed admiration for China's
national defense modernization.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the meeting were Vice-Chairman of
China's Central Military Commission Chi Haotian, who also serves
as a state councillor and minister of national defense, and Xiong
Guangkai, deputy chief of the General Staff of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
