<HEADLINE> Turkey, Kuwait to Sign Two Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait and Turkey will
sign an agreement on the prevention of double taxation and a
cultural exchange program during a visit by Turkish President
Suleiman Demirel to Kuwait due Monday, Turkish ambassador to
Kuwait Ahmet Ertay said today.
</P>
<P>
Ertay told the official Kuwait News Agency that the cultural
protocol is planned to cover the next two years and added that "we
hope this program will help to reactivate the cultural relations
which have been neglected over the years."
</P>
<P>
Demirel's Kuwait visit, which comes in response to an
invitation made by Kuwaiti Amir, would be the second of its kind
since 1991. He last visited Kuwait in January 1993 when he was
Prime Minister of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Ertay described the visit as one "between brothers and
friends," adding that "it will create the opportunity on the
highest level to exchange views on both regional and
international issues that concern both countries.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait attaches great importance to Demirel's visit. Kuwaiti
cabinet expressed warmly welcome to Demirel's visit at a
meeting earlier today, stressing the importance of the expected
meeting of Demirel and Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed
Al-Sabah in further boosting the distinguished bilateral ties
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey supported Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War which liberated
Kuwait from the seven-month Iraqi occupation and adopted a firm
position towards the Iraqi invasion. Since then the two states
exchanged many official visits.
</P>
<P>
Ertay said there are a number of high level visits between
the two countries that are pending and should be realized in the
near future. Trade volume between the two countries is 200
million U.S. dollars, Ertay pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the "visit will help to boost
economic and cultural relations between both countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
