<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Africa Witnesses Economic Recovery in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Chen Cailin )
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 5 (Xinhua) --Economic recovery in Africa
beginning in 1994 continued in 1996 with an average of growth
rate of 3.9 percent in that year, and experts at the United
Nations Conference of Trade and Development (UNCTAD) forecast
that economic recovery in Africa can be expected to maintain its
current growth trend in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The current growth trend on the African continent indicates
that Africa's economy has walked out the gorge which started in
1980s, said the UNCTAD in its 1997 "Trade and Development Report".
</P>
<P>
The significant development of African economy had several
characters: firstly, Africa's economic growth last year surpassed
the average growth rate of 2.8 percent of the whole world, thus
the continent was regarded as the second fastest in its economic
growth in the world, lagging only behind Asia.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, economic recovery has become more widespread in the
continent. In all the subregions, exception of the east and
central Africa, economic growth was faster than in 1995. In 11
countries it reached or surpassed the 6 percent target set by the
United Nations new agenda for the development of Africa in the
1990s, in 28 countries it ranged from 3 percent to 6 percent, in
12 it was still positive but below 3 percent, and in only 2,
their output declined abruptly.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the economic performance in the 33 African Least
Developed Countries (LDCS) was also encouraging last year. These
LDCS registered an average of growth rate of 4.6 percent last
year, 0.7 percent more than the average growth rate of whole
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, the real per capita income in Africa is now
increasing. The fall in Africa's real per capita income that
began in the 1980s continued in the early 1990s, but it witnessed
a marked improvement over the past two years, when eonomies rose
faster than the population growth for the first time in many
years.
</P>
<P>
It is noteworthy that the 5.2 percent increase of agricultural
output in 1996, in contrast to almost no growth in the previous
year, is the highest since the beginning of the decade and has
been the major factor behind the strong eocnomic recovery in
Africa. At the same time, upturns in the prices of banana and
phosphates gained more than what compensated for the fall in the
prices of beverages, metals and non-oil minerals land raw
materials. As a result the region registered an increase of 8.7
percent from export last year than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The economic recovery in Africa was due to peace and stability
prevailed in the continent in the past few years, and the eocomic
refroms and positive readjustment of economic policies in most of
African countries which encourage better economic performance in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the UNCTAD held that there are some favorable
factors for the continuing African economic recovery, as non-oil
commodity prices are expected to increase modestly on account of
favorable movement in food and agricultural raw materials prices
in the world market. Although economies in most African countries
are still fragile, but they predicted that economic recovery will
continue, probably stronger than that in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
