<HEADLINE> More Political Reforms Expected in Nigeria Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state General
Sani Abacha is expected to announce a general amnesty of
political detainees in a nationwide broadcast next month to mark
the 4th anniversary of the current military administration.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution of the country may also be promulgated
into law on November 17, the "Sunday Vanguard" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Abacha is also expected to put to rest all speculations about
whether or not he should run in the 1998 presidential elections,
the report said, quoting a highly-placed source in the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
All these are matters that have been in the expectation of the
nation which, however, was disappointed by Abacha as he mentioned
none of them in his speech four days ago to celebrate Nigeria's
37th independence anniversary.
</P>
<P>
With regard to expressed disappointment by a cross section of
the citizenry on expectations from Abacha's October 1 broadcast,
the source said "the speech was basically a reflection of the
state of the nation, mostly the achievements of the
administration."
</P>
<P>
"But be rest assured that because certain expected
pronouncements were not made does not mean the head of state is
unmindful of the citizens' expectations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lamenting that some people still could not understand Abacha's
style of leadership after four years, the source said: "I can
assure you that before November 17, the head of state could order
the release of some 'lesser' political detainees."
</P>
<P>
The "bigger" detainees shall breath the air of freedom on
November 17 through the magnanimity of the head of state, he
added.
</P>
<P>
In his 50-minute independence broadcast, Abacha spent most of
the time on talking about the achievements scored in the past
four years. He touched some of the problems facing the nation but
did not give any policies and measures to resolve them.
</P>
<P>
Prominent Nigerians and organizations have since expressed
unreserved disappointment over the broadcast which was generally
regarded as lacking substance.
</P>
<P>
The unconfirmed report may to some extent raise hope for the
nation that has been longing for a big stride toward political
reform and economic development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
