Jigme, vice-chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, has called on Hong Kong students to learn
about China's history and culture, while at the same time
concerning themselves with the nation's future, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged the students to fully acquaint themselves with
China's history of over 5,000 years, as well as with the ongoing
reform and opening-up efforts.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Chinese government will firmly
implement the principle of "one country, two systems," Hong Kong
people governing Hong Kong and a high degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
In the final analysis, Hong Kong's long-term prosperity and
stability will rely on participation by its people, said Wang..
</P>
<P>
"Today's younger generation will shoulder the task of building
tomorrow's Hong Kong," he said. "Hong Kong' students must cherish
the nation in the process of deepening their understanding of
their motherland and people."
</P>
<P>
Wang called on the students to make greater contributions to
creating a more splendid future for China's inland areas and Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, organized by the Hong Kong Soong Ching Ling
Foundation and Ta Kung Pao, also participated in October 1st
celebrations marking the 48th anniversary of the founding of New
China. 
