<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Becomes Part of China's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment has emerged
as a major part of China's economic development along with the
increasing influx of foreign capital, according to Wu Yi, minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Wu told participants in today's meeting of the China
Association of Enterprises with Foreign Investment (CAEFI) that
China has continually perfected policies and expanded the scope in
the use of foreign investment in recent years. She said related
efforts have been carried out in accordance with the principle of
active, rational and effective use of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
By the end of August, China had used foreign investments of
204.425 billion US dollars, and approved 296,900 foreign-funded
enterprises. Over 145,000 foreign-funded companies are currently
in operation.
</P>
<P>
The amount of foreign investment flowing into China over the
past five years has accounted for 86.6 percent of the total for
the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
China not only pays great attention to investments by
transnational companies, but also welcomes investments and
technology from small- to medium-sized ones, said Wu.
</P>
<P>
China has opened numerous industries and regions, with some
regions using diverse channels to introduce foreign investment,
according to Wu.
</P>
<P>
She noted that China will continue to exert great effort to
enhance the quality and level of foreign trade by further
perfecting the structure of opening, and using foreign funds more
positively, reasonably and effectively.
</P>
<P>
China is changing from a potential into a realistic market
which will provide valuable investment opportunities for
businesses throughout the world, said Wu.
</P>
<P>
The CAEFI, established in 1987, is a nationwide organization
which serves both Chinese and foreign investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
