<HEADLINE> Mubarak Calls on Arab Nation to Rally for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today called upon the Arab nation to rally behind the goal of
peace as they did in achieving military victory.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab nation is capable of achieving victory in the battles
of war as in the battles for peace so long as its ranks are
rallied, its will is resolved and its intentions are pure and
honest to serve the Arab interests only," the Egyptian leader said
in a televised speech before noon.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the nation marking the 24th anniversary of
the 1973 October War victory against Israel, Mubarak said October
War has significantly changed conditions in the Mideast and ended
the no-war-no-peace state.
</P>
<P>
"One of the most important lessons to be drawn from the October
war was its proof of the Arabs' capability to achieve victory in
all their battles so long as their ranks are unified and their
will is strong," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Under the leadership of late President Anwar Sadat, Egyptian
troops crossed the Suez Canal in October 1973 to recover territory
including the Sinai Peninsula lost in the "Six-Day War" of June
1967 when Israel quickly defeated neighboring Arab states
including Egypt.
</P>
<P>
After 18 days of fighting, a cease-fire was arranged. In 1974
and 1975 the U.S. negotiated disengagement agreements whereby
Israel evacuated territory in Sinai and Israeli and Egyptian
forces were separated by a buffer zone under the control of U.N.
forces.
</P>
<P>
"October victory adjusted the history of the Middle East," said
the president, adding that the military feat proved to the world
that the Egyptians and Arabs would never be "dead meat."
</P>
<P>
The war also showed that military supremacy is not monopolized
by any party in particular and that true security can never be
guaranteed by geographical expansion at the expanse of others, the
president added.
</P>
<P>
"The only guarantee to true security is objective dialog,
mutual trust and peaceful co-existence where the rights of all
parties are protected and respected," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his address, the president accentuated the necessity of full
vigilance to face all perils threatening the security and
stability of the region as well as the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He warned of the absence of mutual trust between the parties
concerned and blamed it on unsound policies that lack common
sense, a sound future prospect and a true commitment to agreements.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak called upon all parties to combine efforts to realize a
breakthrough and resume peace talks on all tracks in the Middle
East as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We pin great hopes on the sincere and constructive efforts
exerted by the friendly major countries that are interested in the
situation in the region and willing to help get the peace process
of the hook," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been blocked for six
months over the Jewish state's building of settlements in the
occupied Arab lands. But the two sides agreed last week in New
York to restart this month formal talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
