<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Voice Pessimism Over Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of renewed
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that the Mideast peace crisis remains in place.
</P>
<P>
In statements to reporters after meeting with President Hosni
Mubarak, Moussa also played downed the pending negotiations under
the brokerage of Washington.
</P>
<P>
"The deadlock in the Middle East peace process is still there
as the Palestinian-Israeli meetings to be held are only small
steps that might not yielded any substantial results," he said.
</P>
<P>
In order to break the deadlock in the process, it is necessary
to seriously dwell on the basic issues such as the Israeli
settlements and redeployment of Israeli troops in Palestinian
towns and others closely connected to the Palestinian problem, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who returned home Saturday from New York, presented a
report to Mubarak today on his visit to the United States and the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
During his ten-day U.S. visit, the top Egyptian diplomat had
discussions with several of his foreign counterparts, including
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who made a recent tour
to the area, her first since assuming office early this year.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the Egyptian stance expressed in his address before
the 52nd UN General Assembly meetings and U.S. officials is that
serious action should be taken by various parties, the Israeli and
Arab parties as well as the peace co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations had been blocked for six
months over the Jewish state's building of settlements in the
occupied Arab land. But the two sides agreed last week to restart
formal talks on October 6 and 13.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said his report submitted to the president included a
number of other issues discussed during his visit such as the
Libyan crisis and the recent Arab League resolution in this
respect.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League is trying to help lift the sanctions imposed on
Tripoli for alleged involvement in the downing of an airliner over
Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988. A total of 270 were killed in the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
As regards enlargement of U.N. Security Council membership, he
said that the third world and non-aligned states agreed that there
should not be any rush just because one country or two wanted to
get a seat in the council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
