<HEADLINE> Beattie Quits Year-ending GP Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Australian Daryl Beattie's sad
year ended in dismay Sunday as illness prevented him from racing
in the season-ending Australian 500cc motorcycle Grand Prix in
Phillip Island.
</P>
<P>
Beattie was to have ridden his last race for the Lucky Strike
Suzuki factory team after being told earlier this month he was not
required in 1998 but he withdrew from the season finale because of
influenza.
</P>
<P>
Beattie has had a frustrating year on a bike he hasn't been
happy with, but team manager Garry Taylor said he had been keen to
race Sunday in what may have been his last ever 500cc GP.
</P>
<P>
Taylor said his team simply could not provide the Australian,
who was second in the world championship in 1995, with the machine
he needed.
</P>
<P>
"To be honest, on another bike he might go better," Taylor
said, "We've gone as far as we can in terms of giving him the bike
he wants, and we really haven't been able to do that."
</P>
<P>
Beattie is now likely to search for a drive in touring
cars. 
