<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strives for Sustainable Development (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the time being, three major river systems -- Huaihe, Liaohe
and Haihe, three lakes -- Taihu, Chaohu and Dianchi, and the areas
suffering two environmental pollutants -- acid rain and sulphur
dioxide, which are widely regarded as national blackspots, have
been designated as major targets on which war against pollution is
to be waged.
</P>
<P>
Results of last year's efforts have begun to show
through. Water from Huaihe River and Taihu lake, to the west of
Shanghai, are potable again, while irrigation of the basin's
farmland with the river's water is now safe.
</P>
<P>
And a further 30.5 billion yuan (US$ 3.75) remains to be spent
on the pollution control project.
</P>
<P>
During 1996, a total of 5,717 pollution-control projects were
completed, with a total investment of 4.24 billion yuan (US$0.52
billion).
</P>
<P>
To preserve the ecological system, China joined "World Union of
Conserving Nature" last year and committed itself to the support
of biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
So far, nature reserves comprise 7 percent of China's total
land area.
</P>
<P>
China is also a signatory to the Vienna Convention for
protection of the Ozone Layer (1989) and the Montreal Protocol on
Substances that Deplete the Ozone Layer (1991).
</P>
<P>
And China is the first country to submit to the United Nations
its Agenda 21 following the Rio Environment Summit in 1992.
</P>
<P>
By year 2000, according to the Ninth Five-Year Plan for
Environmental Protection (1996-2000), China has two objectives: to
limit pollution in 2000 to the level of 1995, and to implement the
China Trans-Century Green Project Plan which focuses on water and
air pollution control.
</P>
<P>
"That means while maintaining the momentum in economic
development from now to 2000, we should keep the growth rate of
pollution index at zero, so some polluted blackspots should be
cleaned up during the period," says Xie Zhenhua, director of NEPA.
</P>
<P>
"Quite simply, the essence of environmentally-conscious
development depends on the efficient use of natural resources,"
says Shi Yulin of Chinese Academy of Engineering Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"On one side we should control population and probe the
potential of human resources, and on the other we should establish
an economic system thriving on reducing consumption of natural
resources and tapping more alternatives." 
</P>
</TEXT>
