<HEADLINE> Timing for River Locking Set for Navigation Hub Project in Guangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Guigang project on the
middle reaches of the Yujiang River in southwest China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region is scheduled to stop the river in
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the Guangxi Hydro-electric Power
Engineering Administration, which is responsible for the
construction work, has been preparing for the action. A group in
charge of preparatory work for blocking has been formed to study
technical problems that may crop up and to get all machinery and
equipment ready.
</P>
<P>
So far, 540 reinforced steel cages and 178,000 cu.m. of stone
have been prepared.
</P>
<P>
Guigang is on the middle reaches of the Yujiang River, a
tributary of the Pearl River that flows through south China. It is
the largest inland port in south China and an outlet for southwest
China.
</P>
<P>
The navigation hub project being built there was listed as one
of the key state projects for the Eighth Five-Year-Plan Period
(1991-95), for navigation, flood-control, and power purposes.
</P>
<P>
The entire project will cost two billion yuan. 
</P>
