<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strives for Sustainable Development (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But more and more ordinary Chinese have realized the importance
of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by Canada's International
Environment Monitoring Co. Ltd. (IEML) on 24,822 people in 25
countries including China, USA, Russia and Japan early this year,
47 percent of the Chinese think that environmental protection
should be prioritized above economic development, while 32 percent
regard the two as equally important.
</P>
<P>
While the survey shows China is in terms of its citizens'
preference for environmental protection, it nevertheless leads
other developing countries in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The survey's findings reflect a new world environmental order
in which once sacrosanct quotas are no longer holy.
</P>
<P>
"It's no longer appropriate to judge an enterprise solely by
profit it achieves," says Mu Guangfeng, deputy director of the
Department of Law and Regulation of the National Environmental
Protection Agency (NEPA).
</P>
<P>
Mu, a prominent environmentalist who has been involved in
drafting most of the country's environmental laws, even goes as
far as to call for a redefinition of GDP into "green GNP."
</P>
<P>
In its calculation, the cost of cleaning up would be taking
from profits with the resultant index being a true indicator of
environmental defense proceeding alongside development.
</P>
<P>
With backing from the very top, that may well be possible.
</P>
<P>
"On no account should we pollute and waste first, and then heal
the environment," says Chinese President Jiang Zemin, pointing out
that during the course of economic construction, the country
should keep environmental protection as a basic national policy
and hold on to sustainable development as a guiding principle.
</P>
</TEXT>
