<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strives for Sustainable Development (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The concept of sustainable development, defined as the
achievement of economic development without victimizing the
benefits of future generations, is the bottom line in the
so-called conflict between D &AMP; E -- development and environment.
</P>
<P>
Mu believes that the conflict is in fact a myth.
</P>
<P>
"The traditional notion of the environment and development
being contradictory is actually incorrect," he says.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, the two may well be antagonistic initially, but later on
both should be in parallel en route towards a single goal --
sustainable development."
</P>
<P>
Laws and regulations make sure development is kept under close
watch. Provisions include the general law of environmental
protection, and specific laws concerning the control of air or
water pollution, and laws and regulations focusing on specific
problem areas.
</P>
<P>
For example, the State Council's 1996 mandate to clean up the
Huaihe River was the first high-handed action targeted at a
regional environmental problem.
</P>
<P>
In carrying out the mandate, all small factories convicted of
"polluting the environment, harming people's health, severely
wasting resources, and not up to specified scale" were shut down.
</P>
<P>
Closures have been widespread despite their unsocial
consequences of making township workers redundant.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March 1997, 62,561 paper mills, tanneries and
their likes, major culprits of water pollution, had been closed
and destroyed -- to prevent use of plant elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
More significant, starting from October 1, 1997, harming the
environment will become a crime under provisions in the amended
Criminal Law of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0088 </DOCNO>
