<HEADLINE> Indian Capital Sees Spurt in Dengue Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- With rains providing ideal
climatic conditions for aedes mosquitoes, there has been a sharp
rise in dengue fever cases in the Indian capital of New Delhi, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to official information, twenty-six dengue cases were
confirmed here on Saturday, bringing the total number of dengue
patients to 110.
</P>
<P>
Doctors here asked people to be vigilant as October is the
ideal month for aedes mosquitoes, which transmit dengue virus, to
breed.
</P>
<P>
People have been told to ensure that rain water does not
collect inside their homes or in neighborhood. Any container,
artificial or natural, in which water accumulates for seven days,
becomes a potential habitat for aedes mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
Last year when the epidemic broke out in the city, the highest
number of deaths were reported during this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
