<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strives for Sustainable Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But now people have come to see the negative impact.
</P>
<P>
Most of the factories are low-invested with the most basic
fixed assets, run by managers with little or no environmental
concern who are reluctant to re-invest profits to purchase
facilities to clean up their waste.
</P>
<P>
Fines have become more operating costs.
</P>
<P>
A small paper mill in the form of a township enterprise may
yield an output of a few hundred thousand of yuan a year, keep a
score of farmers in work and make its owner relatively wealthy.
</P>
<P>
But it might contaminate a whole water system, leaving the
source hostile to irrigation and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Natural resources are not only being exploited, but in a
damaging fashion.
</P>
<P>
In Liupanshui, Guizhou Province, coke-making fills the once
impoverished locals' pockets with cash.
</P>
<P>
Yet operations in the southwestern province are akin to those
described by Charles Dickens in Victorian England, characterized
by inefficiency, smog and industrial disease. Life expectancy of
miners has dropped to around 40 amid prevalent silicosis.
</P>
<P>
China's national average is 70.8 years.
</P>
<P>
"But coke-making pulls nearly 400,000 farmers, 40 percent of
the region's total poverty population, from the hell of extreme
poverty," says a local official.
</P>
<P>
Here again, primary needs of food, water and shelter seem to be
a louder cry than defense of the environment.
</P>
<P>
"If we push the policy of environmental protection to such an
extent that basic living for the common people cannot be
guaranteed, the policy just won't fly," says an environmental
scientist.
</P>
</TEXT>
