<HEADLINE> Government Says Number of People Missing in Jaffna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government said
today that the total number of people allegedly missing after
being arrested by the troops or police in Jaffna Peninsula was
reduced from 2,568 to 730, due to the finding that some of the
names were duplicated.
</P>
<P>
In a news release this afternoon, the government said that the
Board of Investigations, established in November 1996, found that
the actual number of people alleged to have disappeared was 730.
</P>
<P>
The drastic drop from 2,568 was due to the fact that some of
the names had been reported many times. In one case, there were 98
reports of missing regarding the same person that was alleged to
have been arrested by the army.
</P>
<P>
Since June 1996, various international committees and
non-governmental organizations have reported to the Sri Lankan
government that many people disappeared after they were arrested
by the military or police, or after they were last seen at
barricades, road blocks, security camps or police stations.
Investigations are still underway to trace the whereabouts of
those alleged to be still missing, the news release added.
</P>
</TEXT>
