<HEADLINE> Weekly Review on Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Last week's rally on the
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) was short-lived and speculatives
reacted sharply, bringing down the Sensitive Index (Sensex) by
over 77 points on renewed selling pressure and in the absence of
institutional buying during the week to October 3.
</P>
<P>
The week, which had only four sessions due to a national
holiday on October 2, saw restricted movements showing small
changes in the Sensex, except for the last day (Friday) that
witnessed heavy bull liquidation, partly induced by the suspension
of trading on the National Stock Exchange (NSE).
</P>
<P>
However, the hesitant approach taken by foreign funds and
domestic institutions kept the bulls under pressure.
</P>
<P>
In addition, tension in the Line of Control in Kashmir
following exchange of heavy shellings between Indian and Pakistan
troops during the week also affected the sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The BSE Sensex moved in a narrow range of 3,964.03 and
3,833.92, before closing the week at 3,847.73 as against the last
weekend close of 3,925.24, showing a fall of 77.51 points.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-100 index dropped to end the week at 1,669.46 from
1,703.63 in the previous weekend, netting a loss of 34.17 points.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the Dollex were quoted substantially down at
the weekend at 373.50 and 171.92 compared to the last weekend
close of 380.01 and 174.67 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of business during the week was sharply lower
at 0.98 billion US dollars from the turnover of 1.15 billion US
dollars in the last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
