<HEADLINE> Shanghai's International Mobile Communications Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- An international mobile
communications show will be held here from June 24 to 27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The show is designed to promote technical exchanges and
cooperation between Chinese and foreign telecommunications
companies.
</P>
<P>
In the past ten years, the number of mobile phone subscribers
in China topped 10 million and the digital telephone network was
directly connected with 12 countries and regions. China has caught
up with Germany and Japan, with a total capacity of 100 million
lines for public telephones, and ranks second, after the US.
</P>
<P>
There are now 7.3 phones for every 100 people, and as many as
25 for every 100 in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992 the telecommunications industry in Shanghai has had
an annual growth of 25 percent and has become a leading sector for
local economic development. During the first eight months of this
year, the output value of the city's telecommunications sector
shop up 40 percent over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, the country plans to spend nearly 100 billion yuan
on fixed assets in the post and telecommunications sector annually
and will increase the capacity of public switching networks to 174
million lines, providing 10 phones for every 100 people and 40 in
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the number of mobile phone users is expected to
rise to 18 million, and the length of long-distance optic-fiber
lines to extend from the current 150,000 km to 200,000 km and the
total number of satellite ground stations to 40. 
</P>
</TEXT>
