<HEADLINE> IFC Expands Investments in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation's (IFC) investments in Egypt has risen by 18.2 percent
over last year to reach 195 million U.S. dollars, said the IFC
report for fiscal year ending on June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The IFC, a member of the World Bank Group with 172 member
countries, is the world's largest multilateral source of loans and
equity financing for private financing projects in the developing
world.
</P>
<P>
This year, IFC is responding to the increase in economic
activity in Egypt by approving seven projects that total 117.15
million dollars targeted on the financial sector, tourism and
industry, according to the IFC annual report available here.
</P>
<P>
The IFC invested 5 million dollars in the Egypt Trust
Investment Fund, one of the first international portfolio funds to
be set up for investment in Egyptian securities.
</P>
<P>
In the petrochemical field, the IFC extended a 5 million dollar
loan to finance the expansion of Alexandria Carbon Black Co.,
Egypt's first carbon black production plant, supplying tire
manufacturers and other rubber firms..
</P>
<P>
IFC's involvement with Orascom Projects and Touristic
Development (OPTD), will be the second tourist project to receive its
support in Egypt. The OPTC will use the 20 million-investment to
expand integrated tourist resort on the Red Sea Coast.
</P>
<P>
In fiscal 1997, the IFC is also funding four manufacturing
projects. It has set aside 35 million dollars to the Egyptian
Cement Co. to build and operate a 2.8 million tonne per annum
cement plant in Suez..
</P>
<P>
Since 1976, the IFC has approved investments in 49 projects in
Egypt with 750 million dollars. Currently, it has equity
participation in 18 Egyptian companies, according to the Middle
East Times.
</P>
<P>
Since its founding in 1956, IFC has committed more than 21.2
billion dollars in fiancing for its own account and has arranged
15 billion dollars in syndications and underwriting for 1,852
companies in 129 developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
