<HEADLINE> Indian Central Bank Chief Optimistic about Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Governor of the Reserve Bank
of India Chakravarty Rangarajan has expressed optimism about the
performance of the Indian economy, saying that it will improve in
the second half of the current fiscal year (from April 1997 to
March 1998), the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The overall economy will show an improvement in the second
half of 1997-98," Rangarajan was quoted as saying at a meeting on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said that there has been substantial increase in bank
deposits and interest rates have shown a steady decline.
</P>
<P>
"These, coupled with tax incentives given in the government's
1997-98 budget and a better prospect for export growth, should
help accelerate the industrial growth," he added.
</P>
<P>
The governor made the remarks on the background that the Indian
economy, especially industry and exports, has registered sustained
slowdown in growth over the past year.  
</P>
