<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: China Strives for Sustainable Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- For almost two decades, China's
GDP, a conventional yardstick of a country's economic performance,
has witnessed an average annual growth rate of 10 percent or
higher.
</P>
<P>
While many are pleased with the progress the figure indicates,
decision-makers with foresight are no longer ease at mere GDP
growth. They are more and more conscious of the seemingly two
antagonistic conceptions: development or environment.
</P>
<P>
So far, China's development in this, the last decade of the
century, has outpaced many other nations' growth rate.
</P>
<P>
But no sooner have the Chinese got a nose for consumerism --
their first refrigerators, reliable power supplies and the lucky
few, family cars -- does the country find itself harboring a
severely damaged environment.
</P>
<P>
From Shenyang's choking air to the Huaihe River's stinking
water, from spreading deserts of Xinjiang to dwindling acreages of
farmland around Shanghai, the problems of urbanization,
industrialization, and intensive agricultural techniques have
rapidly combined to warn government planners as well as individual
citizens that sustainable development, which emphasizes
environmental protection in the efforts to achieve economic
growth, is the only road ahead.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the rural environment, village and township
enterprises, whose industrial output value amounts to as much as
42 percent of the country's total, are constituting major
headaches.
</P>
<P>
In the mi-1980s, these small-medium sized, low-tech operations
were hailed as creators of jobs to absorb surplus agricultural
labor force.
</P>
<P>
They also gave potential entrepreneurs a stage to flex their
long-dormant business acumen, and spared cities from even greater
influxes of migrant workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea's Shipbuilding Orders to Total $10 Billion in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korean shipbuilders' order
receipts are expected to reach 10 billion U.S. dollars this year,
according to industry sources today.
</P>
<P>
Orders received by the nation's top five shipbuilders,
Hyundai, Daewoo, Samsung, Halla and Hanjin, amounted to 5.31
billion dollars in first eight months this year, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Given the 4.5 billion dollars in contracts about to be
concluded and the 500 million dollars in additional contracts
anticipated by the end of this year, the orders are set to surpass
the 10 billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
At present, Hyundai secured 1.2 billion dollars of intent
letters from world major shipping firms, followed by Samsung with
1.1 billion dollars. Daewoo garnered 800 million dollars, while
Halla and Hanjin held each about 500 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Amid the severe slump in shipping prices worldwide, South
Korean shipbuilders' remarkable business records were attributed
to a sharp depreciation of the nation's won currency and the
growing number of orders placed by foreign shipping companies with
South Korean shipbuilders, as Japanese shipbuilders have already
secured orders to last until 1999, the sources noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
