<HEADLINE> South China City Protecting Cultural Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the capital of
south China's Guangdong province, has increased efforts to protect
its cultural relics, adding the item to its plan for urban
construction and annual budget.
</P>
<P>
This year, it plans to use eight million yuan (960,000 US
dollars) for restoration work and three million yuan for relics
collection, double last year's figures.
</P>
<P>
The city government has also raised 53 million yuan for a
special project to repair the Memorial Hall to Sun Yat-sen. The
project is due to start this year.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou is one of the first group of cities designated by the
State Council, with its 122 protected sites, 16 of which are under
national protection, and 28 under provincial protection.
</P>
<P>
The city government has also focused on combating tomb robbery,
relics smuggling and illegal sales.
</P>
<P>
In May, Guangzhou police stopped the robbery of 25 ancient
tombs in the Hengzhigang area, which has an important tomb group
from the Western Han Dynasty, dating back about 2,000 years. The
police have recovered 32 stolen relics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
