<HEADLINE> Hamas Prepares to Live With Jews: Yassin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas) founder, said Saturday night that he
was ready to coexist with Israelis as long as Palestinian rights
are respected.
</P>
<P>
Yassin, who was freed from life imprisonment here and flown
to Jordan three days ago, expressed his hope of coexistence
in an interview broadcast on Israel Television Channel 1's
Arabic-language service.
</P>
<P>
"We have a people, four million Palestinians in the diaspora,
who want to return to the homes from which they were expelled,
therefore we are prepared to live with the Jews, the best life,
in brotherhood and cooperation and coexistence, on condition they
do not gobble up our rights," Yassin stressed.
</P>
<P>
"We do not attack anybody. We do not oppress anyone,"
said the wheel-chaired Yassin, who is expected to return to
the Gaza Strip in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
Although he is nearly blind and speaks in a weak whisper,
Yassin, at 61, still commands a respected position in
Hamas. Yassin suffers from muscle atrophy, is nearly deaf, has
chronic respiratory problems and has been confined to a
wheel-chair since an accident in his youth.
</P>
<P>
Yassin told reporters at his hospital bedside in Jordan over
the weekend that he was "not deported "and that he intended to
return to Gaza. He said that he had asked Israel to give him "an
understanding of my right to return because I have a homeland and
I am not willing to abandon it."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Army Southern Command Yom-Tov Samia signed Yassin's
release from prison early on Wednesday. Yassin was flown directly
to Amman on a Royal Jordanian Air Force medical helicopter.
</P>
<P>
Israeli military court sentenced Yassin to life in prison in
May 1989 after he pleaded guilty to manslaughter charges in the
slayings of four Palestinians accused of collaborating with
Israel. He also was given a 15-year sentence for heading an
outlawed organization, incitement and weapons possesion. Yassin
also was suspected of ordering the kidnaping and murder of two
Israeli soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
