<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Trade Minister on Sino-U.S. Economic Ties (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO) is in the
interest of China as well as those of all other countries, and its
desire to enter WTO, which is a multilateral trading system
established on widely accepted international rules, fully
demonstrates its determination to open the country wider to the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Conversely, exclusion of China from the organization for a
long time will not be conducive to the consolidation and strength
of the global multilateral trade system.
</P>
<P>
China's entry into WTO on the basis of balanced rights and
obligations will help creat a more stable environment for
Sino-U.S. trade and economic relations and will benefit both. The
United States, as an important signatory of WTO, should reason
things out, be conscious of the right course of action, keep its
promises, and play a positive role in China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. trade situation mirrors the different economic
structures, development stages, product structures, methods of
trading, calculation methods, and international division of labor.
</P>
<P>
From the market point of view, China's trade system is open
wider than at any other period of history and one side should not
blame the other for being the sole cause of the existing
Sino-U.S. trade imbalance. Factors like particular materials
imported for processing before export, the shift of some
industrial sectors to China by other fast developing Asian
countries, the unique status of Sino-U.S. trade via Hong Kong, the
differences of calcuation of statistics, and the U.S.'s direct
investment in China--all have a direct effect on the
trade imbalance.
</P>
<P>
China's current favorable trade balance is of historical
inevitablility just as was the balance in favor of the U.S. at an
earlier period. Both sides should view the matter objectively and
reasonably and avoid endless quibbling over figures while ignoring
the fact that bilateral trade has benefited both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0107 </DOCNO>
