<HEADLINE> GCC Joint Forces Ready to Help Member States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 5 (Xinhua) -- "The Peninsula Desert Shield"
forces, joint armed forces of the Six Gulf Cooperation Council
states (GCC), is ready to rush to the help of any member country
threatened, a senior GCC military official has said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency today quoted Staff Major General Faleh
Abdallah Al-Shatti, GCC Assistant Secretary General for Military
Affairs, as making the remarks before attending a meeting of GCC
chiefs of staff due today in Doha, Qatar.
</P>
<P>
A GCC plan to raise the Peninsula Shield troops, based in Saudi
Arabia, from 8,000 to 25,000 and to establish a joint early
warning system has been under implementation since last year.
</P>
<P>
The member countries' final aim is to strengthen the
capability of the joint forces that requires purchase of new
compatible radars, missiles and automated communications, command
and control air defense systems.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shatti said the member states have agreed to increase the
number of troops and acquiring highly-advanced weapons, adding
that a new camp for this force would be built in Hafr El-Batin,
northwest of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
He also said the meeting will tackle a wide-range of military
related issues, topped by the establishment of a radar link-up
among member states of Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab
Emirates, Qatar, Oman and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
