<HEADLINE> Zambian Minister Urges Government to Cut Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government will have
to merge ministries, drastically reduce foreign missions,
review education policy and cut rampant misuse of telephones
as part of measures to control outrageous spending for 1997.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Finance Minister Ronald Penza at the
National Budget Conference for Permanent Secretaries in
Livingstons, southern Zambia on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Penza said children of diplomats alone swallowed more than the
entire national recurrent expenditure for all primary schools of
the country, "Zambia Daily Mail" reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot go on helping a few people at the expense of
hundreds of Zambians," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to exercise very severe restrait on government
spending, including wages in the public sector, he said.
Trade unions will have to be made to understand the
government's good intentions to stabilize the economy and bring
down inflation from this year's projected 15 percent to a single
digit, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government is aiming to reduce the
poverty currently at 70 percent to less than 50 percent by the
year 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
