<HEADLINE> Japan Manager Kamo Sacked after World Cup Qualifier Draw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan has sacked national soccer
team manager Shu Kamo after Saturday's disappointing 1-1 World Cup
qualifier draw with Kazakhstan, officials said here today.
</P>
<P>
Football Association of Japan officials made the decision after
the match in Almaty. So far, Japan ranks third in Group B with
five points from one win, two draws and one loss, seven points
behind the group leader South Korea. Now with the poor results,
Japan's hopes for its first World Cup berth now hanging by a
thread.
</P>
<P>
"I believe this move is the best way to turn things around,"
JFA president Ken Naganuma told reporters after meeting Kamo and
assistant national team coach Takeshi Okada.
</P>
<P>
Okada will take control of the side when they travel to
Uzbekistan to play a qualifier on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Naganuma said JFA officials were disappointed in substitutions
made by Kamo in all four qualifying games and in the team
squandering leads to South Korea last week and to the Kazkh side
in the final seconds of play on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Japan, who jointly stage the 2002 World Cup with South Korea,
are in third place in Asian zone Group B with five points from
four matches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
