<HEADLINE> Three Beauties to Represent E. Africa in "Face Of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Three beauties have been chosen
at a glittering show held in Nairobi to represent east Africa in
the final phase of the "Face of Africa" contest.
</P>
<P>
Bidania Barasa (20, Kenya), Hadjah Bushirah (21, Uganda) and
Emma Too (21, Kenya) were chosen from 12 finalists during the
glamorous event on Friday night attended by more than 300 guests.
</P>
<P>
Five judges led by Hubert Woroniecki from New York's Elite
Model Agency were on hand to select the winners from the
finalists.
</P>
<P>
Judge Hubert said that her team had a difficult task selecting
the three since "all the girls were really good and met the
standard modelling criteria of very tall, extremely thin,
immaculate and excellent skin."
</P>
<P>
"Since our task was to come up with only three girls, we had
to use an extra measures -- personality" which include how the
girls carried and presented themselves, Hubert added.
</P>
<P>
Emma Too who is the crowd's favorite is a full time model
while Barasa is an international business student at USIU and
Hadjah is a student at a Ugandan University.
</P>
<P>
The three winners said that they were "very excited" about
winning and Emma said that she planned to put her income to the
family, "to see if I can send my mother (she is on a wheelchair)
for specialized treatment and help pay school fees for my brother
and sister."
</P>
<P>
The three winners will represent the region at the pan-African
final of the M-Net Face of Africa at the Elephant Hills Hotel,
Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe, on February 27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
They will compete against nine other contestants from North,
Southern and West Africa.
</P>
<P>
The 12 finalists had been narrowed down from hundreds of
hopefuls who entered the competition from Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania
and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The other four judges were French international photographer
Patrick Toselli, M-Net's Front Row presenter Khanyi
Dhlomo-Mkhize, Kenyan model, entertainer and musician Joy Mboya
and designer Sally Karago.
</P>
<P>
The show was co-ordinated and stage-produced by Jan Malan
Productions, the South African company contracted to do the job
by M-Net. 
</P>
</TEXT>
