<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Trade Minister on Sino-U.S. Economic Ties (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sino-U.S. relations started to improve since the second half of
last year after going through a period of difficulty, and since
the beginning of this year, there have been frequent exchanges of
visits by senior officials of both countries. These have included
the visit to China of Vice-President Al Gore, of Speaker of the
House of Representatives Newt Gingrich, and of Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright. There have been visits to the U.S. by
Vice-Premier Qian Qichen and Defense Minister Chi Haotian.
</P>
<P>
A Sino-U.S. economic joint commission meeting was held in
September and it will be followed by one of the
Sino-U.S. Commercial and Trade Joint Commission, where the two
sides will discuss ways to strengthen bilateral economic and trade
cooperation. President Jiang Zemin's visit to the U.S. this month
will no doubt have a far-reaching impact on Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
The question of MFN has long stymied the development of
Sino-U.S. economic ties and trade, and the granting of MFN status
to China is at the core of Sino-U.S. trade relations and provides
a fundamental guarantee of bilateral trade development.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress is still conducting its annual review of MFN
status over China in accordance with the laws of the cold war
period, and this has created a feeling of instability among the
business communities of the two countries and has not been conducive
to bilateral trade development.
</P>
<P>
More Americans with vision have become aware of the fact that
only by settling this issue can Sino-U.S. trade relations have a
solid and stable base. We hope that concerned U.S. government
departments proceed from practice, respect the fundamental
interests and desires of the two peoples, and abolish the annual
debate over this issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Nigerian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Nigerian newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Sunday Vanguard
</P>
<P>
-- A general amnesty for all political detainees will form
part of the highlights of General Sani Abacha's fourth
anniversary broadcast on November 17 when a new constitution will
also be promulgated.
</P>
<P>
New Nigerian
</P>
<P>
-- A prominent Nigerian politician and chieftain of the
country's major opposition National Democratic Coalition, Chief
Michael Adekunle Ajasin, died on Friday at the age of 89.
</P>
<P>
-- Residents of many towns in southwest Nigeria's Osun state,
including the capital city, can no long walk freely at night as
nearly all the major streets have now been taken over by
lunatics. 
</P>
