<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-corruption Efforts In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- China's Liaoning province has
demonstrated its determination to stop corruption by officials and
is showing its achievements.
</P>
<P>
It has prepared an exhibition of 25 important instances of
corrupt government officials, some of them being revealed for the
first time. The first group of visitors to the display were all
provincial officials, and also Liu Liying, Vice-Chairman of the
Central Commission for Discipline Inspection of the Communist
Party of China (CPC), and Chen Mingshu, Deputy Procurator-General
of the Supreme People's Procuratorate.
</P>
<P>
Printed materials and confiscated bribes were on display for
visitors. Also available were details of the investigation of the
Liaoning Oriental Securities Company case, in which large
financial losses were caused by dereliction of duty by company
officials.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning set a record in cracking down on corruption in 1996,
says Song Xudong, Deputy Secretary of CPC Liaoning Provincial
Commission for Discipline Inspection.
</P>
<P>
The province has handled 1,324 important corruption cases in
the past five years, with 456 county-level officials penalized and
1,261 officials being stripped of their CPC membership, Song
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
