<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Urged to Formulate Decisive Policy on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
been called on to produce an explicit and decisive policy on AIDS
which would create a supportive environment for AIDS prevention.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Sunday Mail on Saturday, National
Coordinator of the National AIDS Coordination Program Evaristo
Marowa said, "HIV/AIDS continues to have a serious impact on our
nation as 65,939 cases of full blown AIDS were reported up to the
period ending March 31 this year."
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the actual cumulative number of AIDS
cases that occurred in this country during the period under
review is four-fold the reported figure and the cumulative number
of HIV cases are estimated to be more than 1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation is very serious and it needs to be
resolved with a great sense of commitment, dedication and urgency
by all people including individuals and both the private and
public sectors.
</P>
<P>
He said that on average 550 to 600 people die of AIDS and
HIV-related diseases every week and that more than 30,000 deaths
would occur as a result of AIDS this year.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics reveal that there is a significant rise
in AIDS cases in all age groups with the highest rise being
recorded in the 30-39 year-old category.
</P>
<P>
They also show that males are the most affected as they
constituted the highest number of cases in all age groups except
the 15-19 year age group.
</P>
<P>
Marowa said that Zimbabwe is fortunate in that many organizations
including churches, the media, the government and non
governmental organizations have joined hands to fight the
disease.
</P>
<P>
But there is a need to harmonize all the contributions from
these sectors through a sound coordination program, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Green Buses" Operational in South China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The first group of ten buses
running on liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) have been put to use
in Haikou, the capital of south China's island province of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
The "green buses" show a more than 70 percent drop in exhaust
emissions compared with gasoline buses, providing help to the
urban environment.
</P>
<P>
The "green bus" project will cost more than 30 million yuan,
and the city plans to build 18 filling stations and to refit 5,400
green buses.
</P>
<P>
Haikou is the third city in China, following Shenzhen and
Guangzhou in south China's Guangdong Province, to use such
buses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
