<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oil Production To Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- China's annual oil output
reaches 157 million tons following 40 years of development, making
it the world's 5th largest oil producer, and it will reach 200
million tons by 2010, according to Zhou Yongkang, president of the
China National Petroleum Corp.
</P>
<P>
China has 350 oilfields and 110 gas fields, and 24 oil and gas
production bases such as Daqing, Shengli, Liaohe, Xinjiang,
Sichuan, Dagang and Bohai and the South China Sea. It also has
four major oil and three major gas producing regions.
</P>
<P>
Oil output of the Songliao region in 1996 accounted for 38
percent of the national total and contributed a great deal to the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The production of Bohai Bay in 1996 was 36.9 percent of the
national oil output. Xinjiang produced 14.3 million tons of crude
oil last year, 9.1 percent of the national total, and offshore
production was 15 million tons, 9.5 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, annual oil output of east China will be 110
million tons in 2010, and the annual oil output of 53 million tons
at Daqing, the largest oilfield, will stay the same until 2010.
</P>
<P>
Exploration will be accelerated in the west, with oil
production projected to rise to 50 million tons or more in
2010. Offshore oil production is estimated at 10 million tons or
more in 2010.
</P>
<P>
By late 1996, 2.5 million sq.km. of onshore areas had been
opened to foreign companies and 30 petroleum contracts were signed
with 35 foreign companies, worth 770 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
More than 110 offshore contracts have been signed, with about 3
billion US dollars in foreign capital, accounting for 58 percent
of total investment in offshore oil exploration and development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
