<HEADLINE> Iran Says U.S. D'Amato Law Now Into Abyss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran has claimed that the
2-billion-dollar gas deal with French company Total has sent the
U.S. extra territorial law and unilateral sanctions into abyss,
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
IRNA quoted Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi as saying on his
return from the 52nd session of the United Nations General
Assembly on Saturday night that the inking of the deal by Total
was telling a big "no" to the U.S. D'Amato Law for its unilateral
unacceptable norms of practice in the world trade arena.
</P>
<P>
Iran entered into the 2 billion dollar contract with Total of
France, Gazprom of Russia and Petronas of Malaysia to develop a
giant Iranian gas field at the end of September, risking the
possibility of U.S. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Under the D'Amato Law signed by president Bill Clinton in 1996,
the U.S. would impose sanctions on foreign companies investing more
than 40 million dollars in Iran or Libya. The investment cap in
Iran reduced earlier this year to 20 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi stated that "The agreement was a great triumph for
both Europe and Iran", he added.
</P>
<P>
"The accord heralded the era of greater contracts to be
signed in the near future," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
