<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Trade Minister on Sino-U.S. Economic Ties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua)--The upcoming visit of China's
President Jiang Zemin to the United States will strengthen
Sino-U.S. ties and understanding, promote the steady development
of bilateral relations, and no doubt bring new trade
opportunities to both countries, according to Wu Yi, minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
In a by-lined article released today, Wu Yi urges to
cherish bilateral cooperation and make efforts to promote
Sino-U.S. trade and economic relations. Wu looks back on the China-U.S
trade relations and says "it is of great importance to review our
trade relations in the past and seize the opportunity to promote
the steady growth of the bilateral trade links."
</P>
<P>
Exerpts of the article are as follows:
</P>
<P>
Bilateral economic ties and trade have developed rapidly since
the two countries resumed high level contacts and opened the door
for further development of relations in 1972. According to
statistics from China General Administration of Customs,
Sino-U.S.trade in 1996 amounted to 42.84 billion U.S. dollars, 18
times the figure of 1979, the year when the two established
diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
In the 18 years from 1979 to 1996, two-way trade totaled 260.6
billion U.S. dollars. Between 1979 to 1995, the United States was
ranked China's third largest trade partner and in 1996 it moved up
to the second place.
</P>
<P>
According to U.S. statistics, bilateral trade was 63.5 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996 and totalled 376 billion U.S. dollars over
the past 18 years. China became the U.S.'s fourth largest trading
partner in 1996, up from the 24th place in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Despite differences in the two countries' calculation, the
statistics from both sides show the bilateral trade has recorded
an annual growth rate of 18 percent. In addition to the growth in
trade, two-way investment has also developed rapidly in the same
period. By the end of June, the U.S. had 23,250 approved
investment projects in China with contractual capital reaching
36.87 billion U.S. dollars, 15.67 billion U.S. dollars of which
was already in use.
</P>
<P>
China has made progress in direct investment in the United
States along with the country's reform and opening-up program and
plans to continue increasing investment and expanding cooperation
area in the United States in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
