<HEADLINE> South China City Getting Tough With Drug Abuse In Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- South China's Shenzhen, in
Guangdong province, is keeping its eyes peeled for drug abuse in
schools as part of its war against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Education offices, working with the Communist Youth League of
China (CYLC), set up an anti-drug agency to keep campuses
drug-free and an anti-drug campaign with documentary films, photo
displays, speeches, and symposiums have been supported by the
local CYLC committee.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen is Hong Kong's nextdoor neighbor and has seen a rise
in drug trafficking and drug abuse and related crimes. But, by
focusing on drug-dealers, police officers have dealt with 578
cases of drug trafficking in less than six months, confiscating
202 kilograms of heroin, 4,685 grams of opium and 860 grams of
"ice".
</P>
<P>
Police in the city's Longgang District have tried to enforce
anti-drug laws among young people in the area, and the city's
Office against Drugs is considering stricter controls on drug
abuse among workers. 
</P>
