<HEADLINE> Australian Dry Boat Race Postponed due to Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian outback's
world-famous dry boat race, the Henley on Todd Regatta, began
Sunday in Alice Springs after heavy rain forced a one-day
postponement for only the second time in its 36-year history.
</P>
<P>
"There are still some low clouds but my weather map tells me we
hopefully won't have any more rain," race organiser Bill van Dijk
said.
</P>
<P>
The bizarre race, which sees teams sprinting along the dry bed
of the Todd River near the central town of Alice Springs inside
bottomless boats, has gained international fame since it started
in 1962.
</P>
<P>
In May this year the Rotary Club of Staines in Britain copied
the idea and ran a dry boat race on the banks of the Thames.
</P>
<P>
Before the climax of the "Battle of the Boats Spectacular"
there will be a bathtub derby, a backpackers' challenge, boogie
board races, shovelling sand races and drinks' waiter races.
</P>
