<HEADLINE> Satellite Snag Hits Indian Telecom Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Communication is completely
cut off from about 83 stations to the rest of India with the
failure of INSAT-2D, India's most advanced communication
satellite, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, basic telephone services of India's Department of
Telecommunications to remote and inaccessible areas of Northeast
India, Indian-held Jammu and Kashmir, hilly areas of Uttar Pradesh
and tribal areas of Madhya Pradesh have also been severely
affected.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, operations in some other services such as India's
National Stock Exchange are also out of gear.
</P>
<P>
INSAT-2D, launched on June 4 by the French Ariane-4 rocket, was
switched off indefinitely on Thursday following a major on-board
power failure.
</P>
<P>
Because of the snag, the satellite lost its earth lock, a
mechanism that directs the satellite towards the earth. This led
to the halt of normal functioning of on-board transponders.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Department of Space is attempting to allocate some
transponders on alternate satellite to meet the essential and
commercial telecommunication requirements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
