<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Industrial Growth Stalls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's industrial production
was estimated to have registered a 12.8 percent year-to-year
growth in the first nine months of this year, a slightly lower
growth than the same period last year, official statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output registered a 13.5 percent growth in the
January-September period last year, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The country's industrial output in this period was estimated at
over 96,000 billion Vietnam dong (more than 8 billion
U.S. dollars), of which state-run enterprises turned out 48
percent or 46,178 billion dong (3.8 billion dollars) worth of
goods.
</P>
<P>
State-run enterprises' output grew by 10 percent over the same
period last year, while the production of the non-state sector
rose by 10.2 percent and the foreign-invested sector rose by 20.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The lower growth for the period was attributed to sluggish
sales in August and September, especially the sales of electronic
products, condensed milk, knitwear and cigarettes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
