<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> eds-Poverty-2 Feature: China Aims to Banish Poverty to History (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The state has vowed to increase funding for poverty
alleviation. In 1996, of 10.8 billion yuan allocated for this
purpose, a little over 50 percent came from interest free loans.
More than four billion yuan will be added to the figure annually.
</P>
<P>
Local governments are also obliged to put aside money for use
in poverty elimination in their own regions. If they fail to
contribute between 30-50 percent of the sum provided by the
central government, those sums themselves will be cut accordingly.
</P>
<P>
"However difficult local finances are, contributions to the
poverty fund must be committed at the start of each year," Premier
Li Peng said at the 1996 conference.
</P>
<P>
Funds are currently helping to improve roads -- farmers believe
that access brings prosperity to a village. Another focus is
disaster control. Threats of flood and drought are being lessened
by better water conservation, while training courses make the
latest agricultural techniques known to farmers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the central government is giving more priority to
the approval of large and medium-sized projects in hinterland
regions, where the majority of its poverty-stricken populace
reside. Of all projects launched last year, 43.7 percent were
located in the country's central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
Coastal-hinterland cooperation is encouraged to narrow the gap
between affluence and poverty. In 1996, some 2,500 cooperative
projects were signed, involving the transfer of 30 billion yuan in
capital to township enterprises in central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
Last year nine eastern provinces and a number of prosperous
coastal cities were directly called on for more help. Each is
being held responsible for assisting one western province or
autonomous region. Beijing has been "twinned" with Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, while Shanghai assists Yunnan Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: Bangladesh's Garment Industry Thrives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's ready-made garment
(RMG) industry which began from scratch is a success story, though
many had doubted in the late seventies that a least developed
country would be able to cope with the quality and business
standards of advanced Western markets.
</P>
<P>
The RMG industry earned over three billion U.S. dollars in the
last fiscal year of 1996-97, which constituted about 68 percent of
the country's total export earnings. The volume of RMG export from
Bangladesh is likely to increase at a rate of 20 percent per annum
up to the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The RMG industry is now employing 1.3 million people, most of
them women, and turning to be the country's biggest export earner.
</P>
<P>
As the industry develops fast, the demand for fabrics will
surely grow. About 60 percent of woven fabric now used in the RMG
sector are imported from different countries and regions including
India, China, Taiwan, South Korea, Hong Kong, Pakistan, Malaysia
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is currently the 5th largest RMG supplier to the
European Community market and the 6th largest to the U.S. and
Canadian markets. President of Bangladesh Garments Manufacturers
and Exporters Association (BGMEA) Mostofa Golam Quddus said that
his body would make every effort to develop present markets and to
open new markets at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Favorable investment infrastructure, low inflation rate, easily
trainable vast labor force and flourishment of some new generation
entrepreneurs have turned the country's RMG sector into the
highest prospective investment focal point in the South Asia, said
the BGMEA chief said at the opening ceremony of a textile fair
held here from October 2 to October 5.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
