<HEADLINE> Trade Between Chile, Mercosur Expands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Chile and member
countries of the South America Common Market (Mercosur) has grown
since a free trade agreement between the two sides became
effective a year ago, according to the Central Bank of Chile.
</P>
<P>
In the nine months from last October to June, Chile's total
export to Mercosur amounted to 1.32 billion U.S. dollars, up 3
percent over the same period of the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Its total import from Mercosur during this period was valued at
2.19 billion dollars, representing an 8 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Farm and animal husbandry exports registered a high growth rate
of 11.2 percent, compared with the 3.3 percent growth in the
country's export to other regions of the world.
</P>
<P>
The trade was stimulated by the reduction of tariffs. Under the
free trade agreement signed in June 1996, the average tariff for
Chilean exports to and imports from the Mercosur states should be
reduced to 3.2 percent and 5.7 percent respectively from the
original 8.2 percent and 11 percent as of October 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
