<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Economic Downturn Drives up Suicide Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Thai mental health experts
believe that the country's economic downturn is a significant
factor in the increase of suicide cases in recent months.
</P>
<P>
At a time when there is no security of employment and business
opportunities and economic revival is not yet in sight, people,
particularly those who are deeply in debt and are paying
installments for their housing or vehicles, often feel frustrated
and may decide to take their own lives as a way to end all their
worries.
</P>
<P>
Many people found it difficult to adjust to the suddenness with
which security and affluence changed to debt, bankruptcy and
worry.
</P>
<P>
Since the float of the baht in early July, the Thais are worse
off by as much as more than 40 percent in terms of U.S. dollars,
apart from higher cost of living, rising prices, factory closures
and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted in late August by the Mental Health
Department of the Public Health Ministry shows that people in the
property and finance sectors, the two most seriously ailing
sectors, are prone to stress and depression, which could induce
suicidal tendencies.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicates that of the 410 respondents from various
occupations, 75 percent had financial problems. When people are
unable to cope with long-term economic problems, they are likely
to feel depressed and desperate and even 'punish' themselves by
taking their own lives.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Bandit Sornpaisal, chief of the Work System Reform Office,
listed four major risk groups.
</P>
<P>
The unemployed, who may not yet feel heavy stress now because
they still have some money left in their pockets, will feel it in
the next few months when their savings run out and when consumer
prices rise further.
</P>
<P>
Business people, in particular those in the property and
finance sectors, will be over-stressed from debt problems and
bankruptcy. The stress will also affect their employees and family
members.
</P>
<P>
The uneducated are often at a loss what to do to manage their
lives and how to solve their problems. Those people often do not
have affluent relatives to turn to for help.
</P>
<P>
Divorcees, already hurt by failed marriages, do not have a
spouse to share the economic woes and to get moral and financial
support.
</P>
<P>
In terms of income, Dr. Bandit said high income-earners,
especially those who earn more than 100,000 baht (2,700 U.S.
dollars) a month, are vulnerable because they cannot adjust
readily to sudden changes in their lives.
</P>
<P>
These people have gotten used to all kinds of convenience and
luxury. When they lose them, they feel that they have lost
everything and do not want to live any more.
</P>
<P>
The Mental Health Department has urged the media, monks and
astrologers to try to boost the morale of those in trouble,
encourage them to live on and not to commit suicide to orphanize
their children and leave more burden to their relatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
