<HEADLINE> Australian PM Reshuffles His Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard reshuffled his cabinet today following a two-week
government crisis.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister announced today his new ministry, dumping
Employment Minister Amanda Vanstone from cabinet and promoting
junior minister David Kemp to her portfolio. Senator Vanstone has
been demoted from cabinet to the junior portfolio of Minister for
Justice.
</P>
<P>
In other major changes, National Party MP Mark Vaile will
become minister for transport and regional development, and former
sports minister Warwick Smith will replace Judi Moylan as family
services minister, the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Moylan was demoted to Minister for the Status of Women, while
Federal Treasurer Peter Costello, Trade Minister Tim Fischer and
Workplace Relations Minister Peter Reith all retained their
positions.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister John Fahey will become the minister for
Finance and Administration, with the Department of Administrative
Services abolished and its functions divided among several other
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
Industry Minister John Moore will take on the responsibility
for science.
</P>
<P>
National Party MP Warren Truss was named new Customs and
Consumer Affairs Minister and Deputy Leader of the House, Alex
Somlyay, as the junior minister for Regional Development,
Territories and Local Government.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Thomson, parliamentary secretary to Foreign Affairs
Minister Alexander Downer, was appointed Minister of Sport,
Tourism and the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Senator Chris Ellison replaces David Kemp as the junior
minister for Schools, Vocational Education and Training.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was forced to reshape his cabinet following
the resignation late last month of former Transport Minister John
Sharp and Administrative Services Minister David Jull after
revelations that Sharp secretly repaid around 6300 U.S. dollars in
travel claims.
</P>
<P>
Science Minister Peter McGauran later resigned after he was
also forced to repay dubious travel claims, and question-marks
were raised over Veterans Affairs Minister Bruce Scott's claims.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
