<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> eds-Poverty-3 Feature: China Aims to Banish Poverty to History (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To improve the management of poverty elimination work, the
state now holds individual provincial governments responsible for
the planning and implementation of initiatives. Formerly, decision
making power and responsibilities rested with Poverty Alleviation
and Development Office (PADO) and similar offices at all levels.
</P>
<P>
"Every top official should go and spend several days in a
number of impoverished villages before they make decisions
concerning poverty alleviation," said President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
International cooperation is welcome and sought after. The
first phase of World Bank assisted projects, launched at the end
of 1995, involved a loan of 250 million U.S. dollars which was
allocated to 35 counties in southwest China, aiding 3.5 million
impoverished people.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Fuhe, a divisional chief of PADO, the second
phase of World Bank projects, involving 180 million U.S. dollars
in loans, has gained approval and will begin in 1998 with funds
to be directed to Sichuan, Shaanxi, and Ningxia. The initiative
aims to lift 2.6 million people in 26 counties above the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
While international help is growing, all domestic social forces
are being mobilized. Many state departments launched various
aid-the-poor campaigns with various names.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission is mounting its "Project of
Eliminating Poverty by Promoting Education;", the Ministry of
Agriculture has a "Harvest Plan" while the "Spark Plan" of the
State Commission of Science and Technology aims to promote the
spread of agrotechniques.
</P>
<P>
Various non-governmental institutions are also active in the
endeavor, making contributions to programs such as Project Hope
which helps poor children complete their education.
</P>
<P>
China succeeded in helping seven million people out of poverty
last year. "We are confident of lifting 10 million people above
the poverty line this year," says Liu Fuhe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
