</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazilian imports of Argentine oil reached
658.2 million U.S. dollars in the first eight months of the year,
a 20 percent increase compared to the same 1996 period, said the
Petroleos de Brazil (Petrobras) state company.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian imports could reach 150,000 barrels a day this year,
a big increase from the 6,000 barrels a day in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Argentina replaced Saudi Arabia as the main oil supplier for
Brazil last year.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil registered an 800 million dollar trade
deficit with its Mercosur partners in the first eight months of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The imports reached 6.4 billion dollars and exports earned 5.6
billion dollars, says a report from the Brazilian Industry,
Commerce, and Tourism Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Brazil-Mercosur trade increased 22.4 percent during the
January-August period of this year, compared to the same period of
1996.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Banco Real, one of the 10 most important
financial institutions of Brazil, has started procedures to
operate as a retail bank in Argentina, the Central Bank of
Argentina (BCA) said on September 30.
</P>
<P>
Banco Real, according to BCE, has run an investment bank
in Argentina since the beginning of the 1980s through its Buenos
Aires office with assets worth 45.5 million dollars and liabilities
totaling 19.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazilian foreign reserves shrank 1.7 percent
(1.1 billion dollars) between August and September, said the
Central Bank in its last statistics report.
</P>
<P>
The hard currency reserves dropped from 63 billion dollars in
August to 61.9 billion dollars in September. 
</P>
