<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up:  Economic Cooperation Between Myanmar and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The bilateral economic
cooperation between Myanmar and Singapore has strengthened
further following a two-day visit to Singapore by Myanmar leader
Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt.
</P>
<P>
First secretary of the State Law and Order Restoration Council
(SLORC) Khin Nyunt, who ended his visit Saturday, attended in
Singapore the second meeting of the two countries' Joint
Ministerial Working Committee (JMWC) on Promotion of Economic
Cooperation, Trade and Investment.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, two agreements were signed. One was the
Maritime Transport Agreement between the two countries, the
another one was an Agreement of Cooperation between the Union of
Myanmar Chamber of Commerce and Industry and the Singapore
Federation of Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
The economic cooperation between Myanmar and Singapore has
developed rapidly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In March 1994, Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong visited
Myanmar, prompting a large volume of Singapore investment in
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The two countries initiated an agreement on bilateral economic
cooperation during a visit to Singapore by Myanmar SLORC Chairman
Senior-General Than Shwe in June 1995.
</P>
<P>
Later in January 1996, a high-ranking Singapore economic
mission, led by Minister of Trade and Industry Yeo Cheow Tong,
came to Yangon where the first meeting of the two countries' JMWC
on the cooperation was held.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996 meeting, the two sides explored new areas of
cooperation in investment, tourism, agro-business and human
resources development. They also reached a new aviation accord
amending the old one signed in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-1996, Singapore private sector has been engaged in
development of Myanmar's Thanlyin-Kyauktan industrial zone, 50
kilometers south of the capital of Yangon, with three firms
building 10 container wharves out of 17 at the zone's Thilawa
Port.
</P>
<P>
Some Singapore companies are also building factories in another
industrial zone of Hlaingtharya in the capital to produce
galvanized iron sheets for export.
</P>
<P>
Singapore invested in the most of the 39 foreign-invested
hotels and tourism projects in Myanmar. The latest involvement in
the sector was the building of a beach resort hotel at Palongitan
island in Kawthaung, the southern end of Myanmar bordering
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
To help Myanmar improve its tourism industry, Singapore Tourist
Promotion Board and Singapore Hotel Association Training Education
Center are providing training for Myanmar trainees on hotel
management and communication skills.
</P>
<P>
Trainees from Myanmar's five ministries, the Chamber of
Commerce and Industry and private firms are also receiving
training in export marketing strategies and management from
Singapore Trade Development Board.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Singapore also cooperated in agricultural sector. A
Singapore firm reached a contract with Myanmar in December last
year to make reclamation of low-lying areas, cultivation of
high-quality paddy and establishment of rice mills.
</P>
<P>
Singapore plans to set up bio-technology development center in
Myanmar and carry out reproduction and cultivation of vegetable,
fruit and high-quality rice for exporting to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Singapore, one of Myanmar's five major trading partners, has a
trade volume of 467.75 million U.S. dollars with Myanmar in the
1995-96 fiscal year, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that Singapore's investment in Myanmar
amounted to 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in 56 permitted projects by
the end of July this year, ranking second after the United Kingdom
out of Myanmar's 6.36-billion-dollar total foreign investment from
22 countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Ambushes Kill 32 Police in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A total of 32
policemen were killed in two ambushes in eastern Colombia by
suspected rebels in the past two days, the National Command said
here today.
</P>
<P>
In Saturday's attack on a strong police patrol near the town of
San Juan de Arama in Meta Department, 21 policemen were killed and
four were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Another ambush Friday left 15 people dead. Among them were 11
policemen.
</P>
<P>
The National Command blamed the second attack on rebels
opposing the forthcoming municipal elections, but they were unable
to determine the perpetrators of the first attack so far.
</P>
<P>
The heavily jungled Meta Department is a stronghold of the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, which is calling for a
boycott of the October 26 municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 candidates and 31 politicians have been killed in
pre-election violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
