<HEADLINE> South Koreans Interested in Power Plant Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The South Koreans have shown
keen interest in investing in power plant projects in Sri Lanka,
President of Sri Lanka-Korea Economic Cooperation Committee
Lakshman Watawala said today.
</P>
<P>
A South Korean delegation was on its annual visit to Colombo
last week to promote mutual business interest and explore new
trade opportunities between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The delegates have expressed their interest in investing in a
115 mega-watt power plant in Sri Lanka, which is open for 100
percent foreign ownership.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government is in the process of getting cabinet
approval for the project.
</P>
<P>
Thilan Wijesinghe, director general of the Board of Investment
of Sri Lanka, said there was an urgent need to expand and improve
the transport and telecommunications networks, harbors, power
generation and other infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the budgetary constraints and defense spending,
investment in infrastructure such as power and roads were far from
enough.
</P>
<P>
To increase investment in infrastructure, the Sri Lankan
government has agreed to create opportunities for both foreign and
local investments in infrastructure development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
