<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Lawmakers Reject U.S. Pressure on Judiciary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian Congressmen have rejected
the United States' pressure on Peruvian judicial processes.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian legislators said in statements published by the Lima
press today that Peru's sovereignty is above any kind of pressure
and they cannot accept U.S. intervention in Peruvian Judiciary
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. Congressmen delegation is in Peru to meet Peruvian
authorities mainly to discuss the imprisonment of Lori Berenson,
who was sentenced to life jail nearly two years ago for her links
with the rebel Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian Congress' second vice-president, Oswaldo Sandoval,
said that this is another of the much repeated incidents of the
U.S. State Department meddling in the domestic affairs of Peru.
</P>
<P>
"Peru does not need the tutorship of any foreigner to solve
problems such as terrorism," Sandoval said.
</P>
<P>
"This (U.S.) congress delegation should explain to its people
that there are countries like Peru where any act of terrorism as
the one committed by Lori Berenson is punished in an exemplary
form," he said.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Ferrero Costa, acting president of the Congress Foreign
Affairs Commission, said that any sovereign nation cannot give in
to pressure from abroad.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Peru Dennis Jett had said that a motion was
tabled in U.S. Congress to cut U.S. financing to military training
in Peru because of the Peruvian conviction of U.S. nationals.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Congressman Bill Richardson arrived in Lima in August last
year to intercede for Lori Berenson to serve her sentence in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. congressmen delegation plans to visit the Yanamayo
prison in the Puno Province where Berenson is detained to assess
the prison conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
