<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> eds-Poverty-1 Feature: China Aims to Banish Poverty to History (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- In rural China, an annual net
income of 580 yuan (about 70 U.S. dollars) currently defines the
official absolute poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Those who earn less than this figure are targets of an ongoing
nationwide campaign under the auspices of the Poverty Alleviation
and Development Office (PADO), which reports to the State Council,
China's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The country has vowed to provide all citizens with enough food
and clothing by the year 2000, now less than 1,000 days
away. "However arduous the task, our determination should not
waver," Chinese President Jiang Zemin said at a national
conference on poverty reduction held in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1970s, China has managed to reduce three fourth
of its poverty population. Its share in the world total poverty
population dropped from a quarter to less than one twentieth.
This is a remarkable feat, given the fact that China's population
has increased rapidly over the same period. It now stands at more
than 1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
However, as the deadline approaches, the work becomes harder. By
the end of last year, China still had 58 million people who live
below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
In the last few years, China has lifted an average of five
million people out of poverty. But to meet its poverty alleviation
target, it will have be about 1.6 times more effective until the
end of the century.
</P>
<P>
China's remaining poor live in the most hostile environments of
its vast territory: in arid regions, on dusty loess plateaus
incised by deep ravines, and in high, inaccessible mountainous
areas, mainly in the country's southwestern, northwestern and
central regions.
</P>
<P>
Landscape and frequent natural disasters have combined to
handicap people's social and economic development in these areas,
bogging them down in extreme poverty. Many of the people
requiring assistance have net incomes of just 300 yuan a year.
</P>
<P>
Some poverty alleviation experts say that the new millennium
deadline can be met: in socio-economic terms the country's
national strength is growing while the social awareness of its
people is heightening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971005.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 </DATE_TIME>
