<HEADLINE> Fresh Quakes Hit Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Italian rescue workers are
scrambling to provide possible help to victims of the latest
string of earthquakes as fresh tremors struck the northern Umbria
and Marches regions last night and this morning.
</P>
<P>
More than 700 quakes of varying magnitude have hit Italy since
September 26 when two quakes in close succession killed 12 people,
left thousands homeless and caused irreparable losses to the
country's artistic and architectural heritage.
</P>
<P>
Emergency services were unable to cope with the growing number
of people forced to leave their homes and the rebuilding of
damaged property, an emergency services spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The recent quakes in the worst-hit regions had forced the
rescuers to start their work all over again "from practically
zero," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the town of Serravalle del Chienti in Macerata, emergency
services superintendent, Marco Agnoloni, urged the people who can
return to their homes to return immediately as the agency cannot
provide enough beds. The new quakes had forced more citizens in
the town to abandon their homes and sleep outdoors.
</P>
<P>
With no prospect of an immediate end to tremors, worries are
growing over the seasonal drop in temperature.
</P>
<P>
In Foligno, more than 7,000 people slept outside last night for
fear of further seismic activities. In the nearby town of
Camerino, about 5,000 people were in need of alternative
accommodation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
