<HEADLINE> Spartak Accuse UEFA Officials of Bias </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Spartak Moscow president Oleg
Romantsev on Saturday accused some officials in European soccer's
governing body of bias against Russian clubs.
</P>
<P>
Romantsev, who is also chief coach, lashed out at Friday's
decision by UEFA's control and disciplinary committee to replay
Spartak's first-round second-leg UEFA Cup match against Sion of
Switzerland because the goals in the Moscow leg were too short.
</P>
<P>
"It's a pure provocation," Romantsev told reporters after
Spartak beat Lokomotiv Nizhny Novgorod 3-2 in a Russian premier
league match.
</P>
<P>
"It's a big disadvantage for some of Europe's elite clubs to
play against us from a financial point of view. Therefore some
UEFA officials are purposely trying to eliminate the Russian
clubs from European competition and for that reason they are
instructing referees to be biased against us."
</P>
<P>
Spartak defeated Sion 3-2 on aggregate after a 1-0 win in
Switzerland and a 2-2 draw in Moscow, but the Swiss side
complained that the goals at the Lokomotiv stadium were 12 cms
short.
</P>
<P>
The match is to be replayed on October 15 but Sion have said
they will appeal against the decision. They say they are not
interested in a re-match and want to be awarded a 3-0 win and
advance to the second round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
